{"title_page": "Ezell's Chicken", "text_new": "[[File:Ezell's 01 (brighter and cropped).jpg|thumb|The original Ezell's on 23rd Avenue in Seattle's [[Central District, Seattle, Washington|Central District]].]]\n\n'''Ezell's Famous Chicken''' is a [[Seattle]] [[fast food]] restaurant. The first restaurant was opened on February 3, 1984, in Seattle's [[Central District, Seattle, Washington|Central District]] neighborhood, near [[Garfield High School (Seattle)|Garfield High School]].<ref name=\"Times\">{{cite news |last=Green |first=Sara Jean |date=February 3, 2007 |title=Ezell's feeds the community more than just chicken |url=http://o.seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2003554579_ezells03m.html |work=[[The Seattle Times]] |accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref> The restaurant chain has 12 other locations in the [[Puget Sound region]], including a location on the [[Microsoft]] campus in [[Redmond, Washington|Redmond]] that opened in 2006.<ref>[http://seattle.bizjournals.com/seattle/stories/2006/09/25/newscolumn2.html Ezell's Famous Chicken spreads its wings by opening on Microsoft's campus - Puget Sound Business Journal (Seattle):<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  In 2015, the chain opened its [[Spokane, Washington|Spokane]] location, its first restaurant outside of Western Washington.<ref>[http://www.kxly.com/news/spokane-news/ezells-famous-chicken-moving-into-spokane/30086838 Ezell's Famous Chicken Moving Into Spokane]</ref> The first international location for Ezell's opened in June 2015, in [[Sharjah]], [[United Arab Emirates]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Ezell's Famous Chicken {{!}} Ezell's Famous Chicken Opens Its First International Location|url = http://www.ezellschicken.com/whatsnew/view/ezells-famous-chicken-opens-its-first-international-location|website = www.ezellschicken.com|accessdate = 2016-01-04}}</ref> The Sharjah location has since closed.\n\nEzell's was made famous when talk show host [[Oprah Winfrey]] called it her favorite fried chicken.  There are a number of photos of her on the wall in the original Seattle location proclaiming her love of the chicken.  It is also said she has the chicken flown to her in Chicago when she has a craving.<ref>[http://www.seattlepi.com/safeco/fans/safe16.shtml Home-team vendors add spice to stadium's Bullpen Market food court]{{dead link|date=November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nThe restaurant was founded by Ezell Stephens and Lewis Rudd, opening its first location on February 3, 1984, in the Central District. The pair, from [[Scottsville, Texas]], discussed opening a restaurant in 1978 after Ezell left the Coast Guard and Lewis left the Army. Stephens and Rudd attended [[night school]] and later earned a loan from the [[Small Business Administration]] to open their store.<ref name=\"Times\"/><ref>[http://www.ezellschicken.com/about.html About Ezell's]</ref> A second location was opened in the [[University District, Seattle|University District]] in 1988, but closed in 1994 after financial problems.<ref name=\"Times\"/> A second round of expansion began in 1998.<ref name=\"Times\"/>\n\n==Departure of Ezell Stephens==\n\nFollowing his departure from the company, Ezell Stephens owned three restaurants in [[Everett, Washington|Everett]], [[Lake City, Seattle|Lake City]], and [[Renton, Washington|Renton]], [[Washington (State)|Washington]].  In November 2011, Ezell Stephens had changed the name of his three Ezell's locations to Heaven Sent Fried Chicken.<ref>[https://mynorthwest.com/74662/he-cant-use-his-name-but-ezell-says-the-chickens-the-same/ Ezell Loses His Name but Keeps the Chicken]</ref> In February 2019, the Renton location of Heaven Sent closed.<ref>[https://www.heraldnet.com/news/heaven-sent-fried-chicken-leaves-renton-stays-in-everett/ Heaven Sent fried chicken leaves Renton, stays in Everett]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of fast-food chicken restaurants]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ezellschicken.com/ Ezell's website]\n* [http://heavensentfriedchicken.com/ Heaven Sent Fried Chicken]\n\n[[Category:African-American history in Seattle]]\n[[Category:Fast-food poultry restaurants]]\n[[Category:Restaurants in Seattle]]\n[[Category:Restaurants established in 1984]]\n[[Category:Central District, Seattle]]\n[[Category:Soul food restaurants]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Ezell's 01 (brighter and cropped).jpg|thumb|The original Ezell's on 23rd Avenue in Seattle's [[Central District, Seattle, Washington|Central District]].]]\n\n'''Ezell's Famous Chicken''' is a [[Seattle]] [[fast food]] restaurant. The first restaurant was opened on February 3, 1984, in Seattle's [[Central District, Seattle, Washington|Central District]] neighborhood, near [[Garfield High School (Seattle)|Garfield High School]].<ref name=\"Times\">{{cite news |last=Green |first=Sara Jean |date=February 3, 2007 |title=Ezell's feeds the community more than just chicken |url=http://o.seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2003554579_ezells03m.html |work=[[The Seattle Times]] |accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref> The restaurant chain has 12 other locations in the [[Puget Sound region]], including a location on the [[Microsoft]] campus in [[Redmond, Washington|Redmond]] that opened in 2006.<ref>[http://seattle.bizjournals.com/seattle/stories/2006/09/25/newscolumn2.html Ezell's Famous Chicken spreads its wings by opening on Microsoft's campus - Puget Sound Business Journal (Seattle):<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  In 2015, the chain opened its [[Spokane, Washington|Spokane]] location, its first restaurant outside of Western Washington.<ref>[http://www.kxly.com/news/spokane-news/ezells-famous-chicken-moving-into-spokane/30086838 Ezell's Famous Chicken Moving Into Spokane]</ref> The first international location for Ezell's opened in June 2015, in [[Sharjah]], [[United Arab Emirates]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Ezell's Famous Chicken {{!}} Ezell's Famous Chicken Opens Its First International Location|url = http://www.ezellschicken.com/whatsnew/view/ezells-famous-chicken-opens-its-first-international-location|website = www.ezellschicken.com|accessdate = 2016-01-04}}</ref> The Sharjah location has since closed.\n\nEzell's was made famous when talk show host [[Oprah Winfrey]] called it her favorite fried chicken.  There are a number of photos of her on the wall in the original Seattle location proclaiming her love of the chicken.  It is also said she has the chicken flown to her in Chicago when she has a craving.<ref>[http://www.seattlepi.com/safeco/fans/safe16.shtml Home-team vendors add spice to stadium's Bullpen Market food court]{{dead link|date=November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nThe restaurant was founded by Ezell Stephens and Lewis Rudd, opening its first location on February 3, 1984, in the Central District. The pair, from [[Scottsville, Texas]], discussed opening a restrautant in 1978 after Ezell left the Coast Guard and Lewis left the Army. Stephens and Rudd attended [[night school]] and later earned a loan from the [[Small Business Administration]] to open their store.<ref name=\"Times\"/><ref>[http://www.ezellschicken.com/about.html About Ezell's]</ref> A second location was opened in the [[University District, Seattle|University District]] in 1988, but closed in 1994 after financial problems.<ref name=\"Times\"/> A second round of expansion began in 1998.<ref name=\"Times\"/>\n\n==Departure of Ezell Stephens==\n\nFollowing his departure from the company, Ezell Stephens owned three restaurants in [[Everett, Washington|Everett]], [[Lake City, Seattle|Lake City]], and [[Renton, Washington|Renton]], [[Washington (State)|Washington]].  In November 2011, Ezell Stephens had changed the name of his three Ezell's locations to Heaven Sent Fried Chicken.<ref>[https://mynorthwest.com/74662/he-cant-use-his-name-but-ezell-says-the-chickens-the-same/ Ezell Loses His Name but Keeps the Chicken]</ref> In February 2019, the Renton location of Heaven Sent closed.<ref>[https://www.heraldnet.com/news/heaven-sent-fried-chicken-leaves-renton-stays-in-everett/ Heaven Sent fried chicken leaves Renton, stays in Everett]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of fast-food chicken restaurants]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ezellschicken.com/ Ezell's website]\n* [http://heavensentfriedchicken.com/ Heaven Sent Fried Chicken]\n\n[[Category:African-American history in Seattle]]\n[[Category:Fast-food poultry restaurants]]\n[[Category:Restaurants in Seattle]]\n[[Category:Restaurants established in 1984]]\n[[Category:Central District, Seattle]]\n[[Category:Soul food restaurants]]\n", "name_user": "Strickesel", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed spelling found byWikipedia:Typo Team/moss\u2013 you can help!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ezell%27s_Chicken"}
{"title_page": "Jennifer Pan", "text_new": "{{short description|Vietnamese-Canadian convicted of matricide and attempted patricide}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image = JenniferPan.png\n| image_upright = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date =   {{birth date and age|1986|6|17|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]]\n| disappeared_date = \n| disappeared_place = \n| disappeared_status = \n| death_date =     <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| body_discovered = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates =\n| monuments = \n| residence = \n| nationality = [[Canadian]]\n| other_names = \n| citizenship = Canada\n| education = [[Mary Ward Catholic Secondary School]] (did not graduate)\n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = \n| years_active = \n| employer = \n| organization = \n| agent = \n| known_for = \n| notable_works = \n| style = \n| home_town = \n| salary = \n| net_worth = \n| height = \n| weight = \n| television = \n| title = \n| term = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| party = \n| movement = \n| opponents = \n| boards = \n| religion = \n| denomination = \n| criminal_charge = {{ublist|First-degree murder|Attempted murder|Conspiracy to commit murder}}\n| conviction_penalty = [[Life imprisonment]] with possibility of parole after 25 years\n| conviction_status = Incarcerated\n| spouse =         <!-- Do not include unless notable or relevant to the crime involved -->\n| children =       <!-- (as above) -->\n| parents = {{ublist|Huei Hann Pan|Bich Ha Pan}}\n| relatives = Felix Pan\n| callsign = \n| awards = \n| website = \n| allegiance = \n| motive = Romantic relationship, monetary gain, alleged child abuse\n| conviction = \n| reward_amount = \n| capture_status = \n| wanted_by = \n| partners = \n| wanted_since = \n| time_at_large = \n| escaped = \n| escape_end = \n| comments = \n| victims = Bich Ha Pan\n| date = November 8, 2010\n| time = \n| beginyear = \n| endyear = \n| country = Canada\n| states = \n| locations = \n| targets = \n| fatalities = \n| injuries = \n| weapons = \n| apprehended = \n| imprisoned = \n| module =\n| signature =\n| signature_size =\n| signature_alt = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Jennifer Pan''' (born 17 June 1986) is a [[Vietnamese Canadians|Vietnamese-Canadian]] woman of [[Chinese people|Chinese]]-[[Vietnamese people|Vietnamese]] ancestry convicted of a 2010 [[Contract killing|kill-for-hire]] attack targeting both of her parents, in response to their allegedly abusive \"[[tiger parenting]]\" into her mid-20s. The crime took place at the Pan residence in [[Unionville, Ontario|Unionville]], [[Markham, Ontario|Markham]], [[Ontario]], in the [[Greater Toronto Area]]. Jeremy Grimaldi, a journalist of the ''[[Markham Economist & Sun]]'' and the author of ''[[A Daughter's Deadly Deception: The Jennifer Pan Story]]'', stated that the affair \"captivated many, if for nothing else than the sheer intrigue of a case involving [[matricide]], a rarity in Canada.\"<ref name=Grimaldi18years>{{cite news|last=Grimaldi|first=Jeremy|url=https://www.yorkregion.com/news-story/6163269-carty-gets-18-years-for-his-part-in-markham-s-pan-murder/|title=Carty gets 18 years for his part in Markham's Pan murder|work=[[Markham Economist & Sun]]|date=December 7, 2015|accessdate=September 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nJennifer Pan's mother Bich Ha (pronounced \"Bick\"){{#tag:ref|''Bich Ha Pan'': {{zh|first=c,j|c=\u6881\u78a7\u971e|j=loeng4 bik1 haa4|p=Li\u00e1ng B\u00ecxi\u00e1}}<ref name=ZHnameparents>Source of Chinese names: {{cite web|url=http://news.singtao.ca/toronto/content_column_tor.php?IndexID=2863523|title=\u300c\u4e56\u4e56\u5973\u300d\u88ab\u63a7\u5f12\u6bcd.\u842c\u9326\u5165\u5c4b\u52ab\u6bba\u6848\u5cf0\u8ff4\u8def\u8f49|work=[[Sing Tao Daily (Canada)|Sing Tao]]|date=November 24, 2010|accessdate=September 18, 2018}}</ref>|group=note}} and father Huei Hann Pan{{#tag:ref|''Huei Hann Pan'': {{zh|first=t,j||t=\u6f58\u6f22\u8f1d|s=\u6f58\u6c49\u8f89|j=pun1 hon3 fai1|p=P\u0101n H\u00e0nhu\u012b}}<ref name=ZHnameparents/>|group=note}} were Sino-Vietnamese ([[Viet Hoa]]) immigrants to Canada.<ref name=LauImmigrantDream>{{cite news|last1=Lau|first1=Joyce|title=A murder in Toronto and the dark side of the Asian immigrant dream (book review)|url=http://www.scmp.com/magazines/post-magazine/books/article/2043688/murder-toronto-and-dark-side-asian-immigrant-dream|accessdate=9 January 2017|newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]]|date=8 November 2016}}</ref> Hann was born and educated in [[Vietnam]], moving to Canada in 1979 as a [[political refugee]]. Bich also immigrated as a refugee. The couple were married in [[Toronto]] and lived in [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]]. Their two children are Jennifer, born 1986, and Felix, born 1989.<ref name=\"Revenge\">{{cite magazine|last1=Ho|first1=Karen K.|date=22 July 2015|title=Jennifer Pan's Revenge: The inside story of a golden child, the killers she hired, and the parents she wanted dead|url=http://torontolife.com/city/crime/jennifer-pan-revenge/|magazine=[[Toronto Life]]|accessdate=9 January 2017}} - [https://torontolife.com/city/jennifer-pan-revenge-simplified-chinese-translation/ Version in Simplified Chinese]<!--Old URL: http://web.archive.org/web/20150722213215/http://www.torontolife.com/informer/features/2015/07/22/jennifer-pan-revenge-simplified-chinese-translation/--></ref><ref name=WangGoldenDaughter>{{cite news|last1=Wang|first1=Yanan|title=Tragedy of 'golden' daughter's fall resonates with Asian immigrant children|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/07/27/tragedy-of-golden-daughters-murder-plot-against-parents-resonates-with-asian-immigrant-children/|accessdate=9 January 2017|newspaper=[[Washington Post]]|date=27 July 2015}}</ref> The Pans found work at [[Magna International]], an auto parts manufacturer in [[Aurora, Ontario|Aurora]], [[Ontario]].<ref name=Revenge/> Hann worked as a tool and die maker, while Bich made car parts. The couple persistently worked hard for their money to ensure that their children had the upbringing and opportunities they themselves had missed out on. Hann and Bich were thrifty and by 2004 were financially stable enough to purchase a \"large\" house with a two-car garage on a residential street in [[Markham, Ontario|Markham]], a town with a large Asian population.<ref name=LauImmigrantDream/> Bich drove a [[Lexus ES 300]] and Hann drove a [[Mercedes-Benz C-Class (W203)]]. They had accumulated [[Canadian dollar|CAD$]]200,000 in savings.<ref name=Revenge/>\n\nJennifer's parents set many goals for their children and had extremely high expectations of them. Jennifer was made to take piano lessons at the age of four, as well as [[figure skating]] classes where she trained most days during the week. She had hopes of becoming an [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] figure skating champion until she tore a ligament in her knee. Jennifer attended [[Mary Ward Catholic Secondary School]] where she played the [[flute]] in the school band.<ref name=Revenge/> According to her high school friend Karen K. Ho, Hann was seen as \"the classic [[tiger parenting|tiger dad]],\" and Bich was \"his reluctant accomplice.\" The Pans picked Jennifer up when classes ended each day and monitored her extracurricular activities very closely. They never permitted her to date boys while attending high school, or to attend high school dances or [[prom]]s out of fear that these activities would distract her from her academic commitments. Jennifer was not permitted to attend any parties while her parents believed that she was attending university. At the age of 22, \"she had never gone to a club, been drunk, visited a friend's cottage or gone on vacation without her family.\"<ref name=Revenge/> Jennifer and her friends reportedly regarded this upbringing as restrictive and greatly oppressive.<ref name=Revenge/>\n\nDespite her parents' high expectations and the fact that Jennifer had received good grades in lower school, throughout high school her grades were somewhat average (in the 70% range) except for music. Multiple times, she forged [[report card]]s using false templates to show her parents that she had received straight As when she had not. When Jennifer failed calculus class in her senior year of high school, [[Ryerson University]] rescinded her early admission. As she could not bear to be perceived as a failure, she began to lie to those she knew, including her parents, and pretended she was attending university. Instead, she sat in caf\u00e9s, taught as a piano instructor and worked in a restaurant to earn money. In order to maintain the charade, Jennifer told her parents she had won scholarships, later falsely claiming that she had accepted an offer into the pharmacology program at the [[University of Toronto]]. She went to the extent of purchasing second-hand textbooks and watching videos related to pharmacology in order to create notebooks full of purported class notes that she could show her parents. Jennifer also requested permission from her parents to stay near the campus with a friend throughout the week.<ref name=Revenge/>\n\nJennifer was actually staying with her boyfriend,<ref name=Revenge/> Daniel Chi-Kwong Wong,{{#tag:ref|''Daniel Chi-Kwong Wong'': {{zh|first=t,j|t=\u9ec3\u5fd7\u5149|s=\u9ec4\u5fd7\u5149|j=wong4 zi3 gwong1|p=Hu\u00e1ng Zh\u00ecgu\u0101ng|labels=no}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.singtao.ca/toronto/2014-05-10/city1399706077d5044769.html|title=\u7537\u53cb\u7206\u6f58\u5973\u66fe\u906d5\u6f22\u6027\u4fb5 \u8072\u7a31\u6536\u8b66\u544a\u77ed\u8a0a \u77e2\u53e3\u5426\u8a8d\u6d89\u6848|work=[[Sing Tao Daily]]|date=2014-05-10|accessdate=2018-09-18}}</ref>|group=note}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/4th-arrest-in-markham-home-invasion-homicide-1.1038532|agency=[[The Canadian Press]]|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]]|title=4th arrest in Markham home invasion homicide|date=2011-04-26|accessdate=2018-09-18}}</ref> a high school sweetheart whom her parents knew nothing about.<ref name=Revenge/><ref name=\"BrownChineseCubs\">{{cite news|last1=Brown|first1=Vanessa|title=When Chinese cubs turn on their Tiger Parents|url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/real-life/true-stories/when-chinese-cubs-turn-on-their-tiger-parents/news-story/36ad884522b2d22ba1e2f88faa5d72ab|accessdate=9 January 2017|work=News.com.au|date=11 December 2016}}</ref><ref>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.com/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT31 PT 31]: \"[...]commenting on the fact that he was only half Chinese. \"[...]you're [part] Filipino.\"\"</ref> Wong was of mixed Chinese and [[Filipino people|Filipino]] ancestry,<ref name=\"BrownChineseCubs\">{{cite news|last1=Brown|first1=Vanessa|title=When Chinese cubs turn on their Tiger Parents|url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/real-life/true-stories/when-chinese-cubs-turn-on-their-tiger-parents/news-story/36ad884522b2d22ba1e2f88faa5d72ab|accessdate=9 January 2017|work=News.com.au|date=11 December 2016}}</ref><ref>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.es/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT31 PT 31]: \"[...]commenting on the fact that he was only half Chinese. \"[...]you're [part] Filipino.\"\"</ref> resided in [[Ajax, Ontario|Ajax]],<ref name=GillisWendyFifth>{{cite news|author=Gillis, Wendy|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/crime/2011/05/04/fifth_suspect_arrested_in_deadly_markham_home_invasion.html|title=Fifth suspect arrested in deadly Markham home invasion |newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=May 4, 2011|accessdate=September 18, 2018}}</ref> and worked at a [[Boston Pizza]] restaurant.<ref name=GrimaldiPT90>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [https://books.google.cz/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT90 PT 90]. \"Daniel Wong is arrested at work in front of his colleagues at Boston Pizza on April 26, 2011.\"</ref> Wong, once a student at Mary Ward, transferred to [[Cardinal Carter Academy]] in North York, Toronto due to low grades<!--\"he was falling behind\"-->, and later studied at [[York University]].<ref name=Revenge/> He was an active [[marijuana]] dealer.<ref name=Revenge/><!--\"he had been charged with trafficking after cops found half a pound of weed in his car.\"--><ref name=Dimannoastonishing>{{cite news|last=Dimanno|first=Rosie|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/crime/2014/09/15/the_fantastic_testimony_of_jennifer_pan.html|title=The astonishing testimony of Jennifer Pan|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=September 15, 2014|accessdate=September 25, 2018|quote=Seven years until Wong \u2014 Pan says he was the one who put her in touch with \u201cHomeboy,\u201d a man he knew through his marijuana dealing}}</ref>\n\n==Adult life==\nWhile pretending to complete her degree at the University of Toronto, Pan told her parents that she had started working as a volunteer at Toronto's [[The Hospital for Sick Children, Toronto|Hospital for Sick Children]], known as Sick Kids. Hann and Bich soon became suspicious when they realized she did not have a hospital ID badge or uniform. On one occasion, Bich followed her daughter to \"work\" and quickly discovered her deception. In a state of shock, Hann wanted to throw Jennifer out of the house, but her mother persuaded him to allow her to stay. As she had not completed high school due to failing [[calculus]], she eventually began working to finish high school completely and was later encouraged by her parents to apply to university. She was, however, forbidden to contact Wong or to go anywhere except to her piano-teaching job. Nevertheless, she and Wong spoke clandestinely during this period.<ref name=Revenge/>\n\nBy the time that Jennifer was 24, Wong had grown weary of trying to pursue a relationship with her. As Jennifer was so daunted and restricted by her parents that she lived at home and only met him in secret, Wong began to date another young woman whom he soon fell in love with.<ref name=Revenge/> Pan quickly invented a new story and told Wong that a man had entered her house, showing what appeared to be a police badge. She then told him that several men had rushed in and [[gang-rape]]d her. After this, she insisted that a bullet was mailed to her, telling Wong that it was sent from his new girlfriend.<ref name=Revenge/>\n\n==Murder==\nIn Spring 2010, Pan was in contact with Andrew Montemayor, a high school friend who, she claims, had boasted in their high school years about robbing people at knife point, an assertion denied by Montemayor. Montemayor introduced her to Ricardo Duncan, a \"[[Goth subculture|goth]] kid\" whom Pan gave $1,500 to kill her father in the parking lot at his workplace. Duncan says that she once gave him $200 for a night out, but that he returned it, and that he rebuffed her when she asked him to kill her parents.<ref name=Revenge/>\n\nPan and Wong were back in contact at this time and according to the police, came up with a plan to hire a professional [[hitman]] for $10,000 to kill her parents, calculating that she would then inherit $500,000. They planned to move in together. Wong connected Pan with a man,<ref name=Revenge/> Lenford Roy Crawford,<ref name=GillisWendyFifth/> Jamaican-born,<ref>Grimaldi, ''[[A Daughter's Deadly Deception]]'', {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA81 81].</ref> whom he called Homeboy, and gave her a [[SIM card]] and an [[iPhone]] so that she could contact Crawford without using her usual cell phone.<ref name=Revenge/> Crawford contacted another man,<ref name=HashamCrownfinishpres>{{cite news|last=Hasham|first=Alyshah|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/crime/2014/08/13/crown_finishes_presenting_evidence_against_jennifer_pan_in_murder_trial.html|title=Crown finishes presenting evidence against Jennifer Pan in murder trial|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=August 13, 2014|accessdate=September 20, 2018|quote=[...]who in turn involved David Mylvaganam, allegedly one of three men who[...]It remains unclear who the other two men who entered the house are. The jury has heard that Crawford and Wong were both at work at the time of the murder. }}</ref> named Eric Shawn \"Sniper\" Carty,<ref name=GrimaldiCartydead>{{cite web|last=Grimaldi|first=Jeremy|url=https://www.yorkregion.com/news-story/8680927-eric-carty-linchpin-in-jennifer-pan-murder-plot-dies-in-jail/|title=Eric Carty, linchpin in Jennifer Pan murder plot, dies in jail|work=[[Markham Economist & Sun]]|date=2018-06-26|accessdate=2018-09-29}}</ref> who in turn contacted Montreal-born David Mylvaganam.<ref name=HashamCrownfinishpres/><ref name=\"LauImmigrantDream\" /> Crawford lived in [[Brampton, Ontario|Brampton]] and Mylvaganam lived in Toronto, while Carty,<ref name=GillisWendyFifth/> who previously lived in [[Rexdale, Toronto]],<ref name=GrimaldiCartydead/> at the time did not have a fixed residence.<ref name=GillisWendyFifth/> The Crown (Canadian government) stated that Mylvaganam was one of the hitmen.<ref name=HashamCrownfinishpres/> Carty was later found responsible for an unrelated murder, and Grimaldi stated that Carty was \"a repeat violent offender\".<ref name=Grimaldi18years/>\n\nThe murder took place at the Pan house in [[Unionville, Ontario|Unionville]], in [[Markham, Ontario|Markham]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/4431797-markham-murder-trial-resumes-with-father-still-on-stand/|title=Markham murder trial resumes with father still on stand|agency=[[Markham Economist & Sun]]|work=[[Guelph Mercury Tribune]]|date=March 26, 2014|accessdate=September 19, 2018|quote=[...]in Unionville in this file photograph. This was the scene of the murder of Bich Pan in 2010.}}</ref> On November 8, 2010, Pan unlocked the front door of the family home when she went to bed, then spoke by phone to Mylvaganam. Shortly afterwards, Mylvaganam and two other people entered the home through the unlocked front door, all carrying guns.<ref name=Revenge/> In the court testimony, the Crown did not establish the identity of the other two hitmen; Wong and Crawford were at work.<ref name=HashamCrownfinishpres/> Carty stated that he was the driver for those who broke into the house, and that he selected them and was involved in plotting the attack. He did not state that he was one of the three or that he directly attacked others.<ref name=Grimaldi18years/> Grimaldi stated that the identity of the triggerperson remains unknown.<ref name=Grimaldi18years/><!--\"To this day, it remains unclear who pulled the trigger,[...]\"-->\n\nAfter demanding all the money in the house and ransacking the main bedroom, the three men took Bich and Hann to the basement where they shot them multiple times. Bich was killed but Hann would survive his wounds. The three men then took all the cash that was in the house including $2,000 from Pan and left. Pan claimed that they tied her up, but that she managed to free her hands and dial [[9-1-1]].<ref name=Revenge/> Hann Pan was treated at [[Markham Stouffville Hospital]],<ref name=Grimaldip17alone>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA17 17].</ref> before being moved to a trauma unit<ref name=Grimaldip27alone>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA27 27].</ref> at [[Sunnybrook Hospital]] in [[Toronto]],<ref name=Grimaldip35alone>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA35 35].</ref> by aircraft.<ref name=Grimaldip27alone/>\n\n== Investigation and arrests ==\nThe evening after the murder, Pan underwent her first interview with the police.<ref name=Grimaldip18alone>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA18 18].</ref> Pan was arrested on November 22, 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/jennifer-pan-plotted-to-have-parents-killed-says-crown-1.2579135|title=Jennifer Pan plotted to have parents killed, says Crown|agency=[[The Canadian Press]]|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]]|date=March 19, 2014|accessdate=September 18, 2018}}</ref> during her third interview at the Markham police station (5 District) of [[York Regional Police]].<ref name=Grimaldiinterviewarrest>Grimaldi - Interview date: {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA66 66]. \"During her third police interview, on November 22, 2016, Jennifer opens up to Detective Goetz[...]\" - Arrest: {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA74 74]. Also {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.cz/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT273 PT 273]. \"[...]Goetz returns before calmly stating, \"[...]At this point of the investigation I will be arresting you for murder,[...]\"\"</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Grimaldi, Jeremy|url=https://www.durhamregion.com/news-story/4489558-jennifer-pan-betrays-her-own-web-of-lies-in-videotaped-interview/|title=Jennifer Pan betrays her own 'web of lies' in videotaped interview|website=[[DurhamRegion.com]]|date=2014-04-29|accessdate=2018-09-23|quote=Ms Pan\u2019s dramatic admission came after more than two hours of questioning in a small windowless room at York Police\u2019s markham station}}</ref> During that interview Pan admitted that she hired killers, but stated that she hired them to kill her.<ref name=GrimaldiIthought>{{cite web|last=Grimaldi|first=Jeremy|url=https://www.yorkregion.com/news-story/4490794--i-thought-you-were-on-my-side-pan-tells-york-police/|title='I thought you were on my side', Pan tells York Police|work=[[Markham Economist & Sun]]|date=April 29, 2014|accessdate=September 22, 2018}}</ref> The interrogating police officer, William \"Bill\" Goetz,<ref name=Revenge/><!--for William--><ref name=GrimaldiIthought/><!--for Bill--> falsely told Pan that he had computer software that could analyze untruths in statements and that there were satellites that used [[infrared]] technology to analyze movements in buildings;<ref name=GrimaldiIthought/> in Canada police are legally allowed to lie to those they are interrogating in regards to the evidence in the trial,<ref name=GrimaldiPT62>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.com/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT62 PT 62]. \"Police in Canada might be allowed to lie to suspects about the evidence they have collected,[...]\"</ref> as well as in regards to the strategies they are using.<ref>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.com/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT50 PT50]. \"In 2000, the Supreme Court of Canada ruled that police are allowed to lie not only about evidence but tactics, as well.\"</ref> Goetz had used the [[Reid technique]] to ensnare Pan.<ref>{{cite news|last=Grimaldi|first=Jeremy|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/insight/2016/11/13/youre-a-good-person-thats-made-a-mistake-here.html|title=The story behind the confession of Jennifer Pan |newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=November 13, 2016}} - An excerpt of the book ''[[A Daughter's Deadly Deception]]''.</ref>\n\nMylvaganam was arrested at the [[Jane Finch Mall]] in [[North York, Toronto]] on April 14, 2011. Carty was arrested at the prison he was held in, [[Maplehurst Correctional Complex]] in [[Milton, Ontario]], on April 15, 2011.<ref>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [https://books.google.com/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT89 PT89]. \"Two days after speaking with Denise Brown, Detective Courtice gives the order to take David down.[...]The following day, police descend on Maplehurst Correctional[...]where Eric Carty is held, and charge him with the same.\" [https://books.google.com/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT88 PT88] states: \"[...]on April 12, when police finally get in touch with Denise Brown,[...]\"</ref> Wong was arrested on April 26, 2011 at his place of employment.<ref name=GrimaldiPT90/> Crawford was the final suspect arrested, entering custody on May 4, 2011 in Brampton.<ref>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA109 109]. Also: {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [https://books.google.cz/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT91 PT 91]. \"Lenford is arrested on May 4[...]Brampton driveway.[...]no further charges are laid in his case.\"</ref>\n\n==Trial==\nThe trial of Pan and her accomplices began on March 19, 2014 in [[Newmarket, Ontario|Newmarket]] and continued for ten months. All pleaded not guilty to the charges of [[Murder|first degree murder]], [[attempted murder]], and [[Conspiracy to murder|conspiracy to commit murder]]. At the trial, [[York Regional Police]] evidence included exhaustive tracking of the mobile device movements and text message traffic, including over 100 messages sent between Pan and Wong in the six hours prior to the killing.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://casefilepodcast.com/case-50-jennifer-pan/|title=Case 50: Jennifer Pan - Casefile: True Crime Podcast|date=2017-04-16|work=Casefile: True Crime Podcast|access-date=2018-02-13|language=en-US}}</ref> Further evidence centered around the atypical nature of the \"break-in\", \"robbery\", shootings, and irregularities in Pan's testimony. Pan's obsession with Wong, her lack of true emotion and a confession regarding the attack, and recognition of the [[Tiger mother|trauma she underwent]] were also detailed.<ref name=\":0\" /> A major irregularity was that Pan was not assaulted, blindfolded, taken to the basement, nor shot, leaving behind an eyewitness to the attack. Evidence from Hann, which differed greatly from Pan's version, also undermined her credibility, as did her inability to recreate the conditions of her 9-1-1 call when her hands were bound behind her (given that the police were the ones who had actually cut the shoelace to release her).<ref name=\":0\" /> The trial included over 200 exhibits; over 50 witnesses testified at the trial.<ref name=Revenge/>\n\nPan, Wong, Mylvaganam and Crawford were all convicted on December 13, 2014, and each received a life sentence with no chance of parole for 25 years.<ref name=\"Revenge\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/toronto/jennifer-pan-toronto-woman-whose-plot-to-kill-parents-left-mother-dead-gets-life-in-prison|title=Jennifer Pan, Toronto woman whose plot to kill parents left mother dead, gets life in prison|author=Paola Loriggio, The Canadian Press|date=24 January 2015|work=National Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/jennifer-pan-sentenced-to-life-without-parole-for-25-years-1.2930113|title=Jennifer Pan sentenced to life without parole for 25 years|date=23 January 2015|work=cbc.ca}}</ref><ref name=GrimaldiLifesent>{{cite news|author=Grimaldi, Jeremy|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2015/01/23/convicted-mother-killer-jennifer-pan-hears-sentence.html|title=Jennifer Pan: Life with no parole for 25 years in murder of mother, attempted murder of father|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=23 January 2015|quote=[...]including a non-communication request from Hann Pan, Felix Pan and other family members, banning Pan from contacting any of them.[...]But Justice Crawford disregarded this and went ahead with the ban.}}</ref>\n\nOriginally Carty was tried with the other perpetrators. [[Edward Sapiano]], Carty's lawyer fell ill,<ref name=Dimannoastonishing/> so around the Summer of 2014<!--\"mid-2014\"--> his case was declared a mistrial. In December 2015, Carty received an 18-year sentence after pleading guilty to conspiring to commit murder. He was to be eligible for parole after nine years. According to Carty, he did not wish to subject Hann Pan to another criminal trial<!--\"[...]said he wanted to put an end to Hann's suffering by pleading out to avoid another lengthy trial.\"-->.<ref name=Grimaldi18years/>\n\n===Penalties and imprisonment===\nJennifer Pan was sentenced to life with no parole for 25 years for the murder of her mother, and attempted murder of her father. Pan's father and brother requested a court order that banned Jennifer Pan from contacting members of her surviving family. Despite the objections of the defense lawyers, the judge filed the order.<ref name=GrimaldiLifesent/> Pan is also barred from contacting Wong.<ref name=Grimaldip314alone>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA314 314].</ref>\n\n{{Asof|2016}} Pan was serving her sentence at the [[Grand Valley Institution for Women]] in [[Kitchener, Ontario]].<ref name=Grimaldip313andPT273>Grimaldi, 1459735250, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA313 313], or {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262 [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.cz/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT273 PT273].</ref> Wong, previously held in [[Lindsay, Ontario]], was at [[Collins Bay Institution]] in [[Kingston, Ontario]]. Mylvaganam was at [[Atlantic Institution]] in [[Renous, New Brunswick]].<ref name=Grimaldip312alone>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA312 312].</ref> Crawford was at [[Kent Institution]] in [[Agassiz, British Columbia]].<ref name=Grimaldip313alone>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA313 313].</ref> Carty, who requested to go to a federal prison in Western Canada or Atlantic Canada, was still at the provincial [[Millhaven Assessment Unit]], awaiting his transfer to a federal prison.<ref name=Grimaldip313andPT273/> Carty, who later moved to Kent, died in his cell on April 26, 2018.<ref name=GrimaldiCartydead/>\n\n==Media reaction==\nAccording to the ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', the case \"sent shockwaves across Canada and the Asian [[diaspora]].\"<ref name=\"LauImmigrantDream\" /> An editorial in the ''[[Northwest Asian Weekly]]'' suggested consideration of the \"idea of recognizing the mental and psychological symptoms that parenting may have gone too far\" in the Pan household.<ref name=\"LoveHate\">{{cite news|last1=Editorial|title=Is it possible to love and hate?|url=http://nwasianweekly.com/2015/08/editorial-is-it-possible-to-love-and-hate-the-strange-case-of-jennifer-pan/|accessdate=9 January 2017|work=[[Northwest Asian Weekly]]|date=15 August 2015}} - [https://search.proquest.com/docview/1706574280 Also at] [[ProQuest]]</ref> A story by Karen K. Ho in ''[[Toronto Life]]'' magazine brought the story to widespread attention by framing it an instance of tiger parenting gone tragically wrong.<ref name=\"Revenge\" /><ref name=\"WangGoldenDaughter\" /><ref name=\"LoveHate\" /> In 2016, journalist Jeremy Grimaldi published a [[true crime]] book about Pan called ''[[A Daughter's Deadly Deception|A Daughter's Deadly Deception: The Jennifer Pan Story]]''.<ref name=\"LauImmigrantDream\" /><ref name=\"BrownChineseCubs\"/> The ''[[Casefile True Crime Podcast|Casefile]]'' and ''[[My Favorite Murder]]'' [[podcasts]] and the ''[[Deadly Women]]'' series also covered the case.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Aftermath==\nBich-Ha Pan's funeral was held on November 15, 2010 and took place at the Ogden Chapel in Scarborough. A funeral for Bich Ha's father was held prior to satisfy a Vietnamese custom that asks for older members of the family to have their funerals first. Jennifer Pan had organized both funerals and had been asked to do so.<!--\"[...]something she later complains her father left her to organize all by herself.\"--><ref>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.cz/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT49 PT49].</ref> Bich-Ha was buried on November 19.<!--\"Three days after burying her mother, on November 22, Jennifer receives a phone call[...]she has to come in again to speak with the police.\"--><ref>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.cz/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT50 PT50].</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bart Whitaker]] \u2013 A Texas man who ordered a hit on his family after he faked continuing attending a university<!--He had dropped out: https://www.cbsnews.com/news/bart-whitaker-execution-reprieve-greg-abbott/ \"Unknown to his parents, the dinner celebration marking his graduation was a fraud. He'd dropped out of school months earlier.\" -->\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n* Grimaldi, Jeremy. ''[[A Daughter's Deadly Deception: The Jennifer Pan Story]]''. [[Dundurn Books]], November 12, 2016.\n** {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262.\n** {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255.\n\n=== Reference notes ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.yorkregion.com/yorkregion-topics/4420090-pan-murder-trial/ Index of articles] - ''[[Yorkregion.com]]''\n* [http://casefilepodcast.com/case-49-moors-murders-part-2/ Casefile True Crime Podcast - Case 50: Jennifer Pan] - 15 April 2017\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pan, Jennifer}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Markham, Ontario]]\n[[Category:People from Toronto]]\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Hoa descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:Matricides]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment by Canada]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian criminals]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of Canada]]\n[[Category:Canadian female criminals]]\n[[Category:Canadian female murderers]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Vietnamese-Canadian convicted of matricide and attempted patricide}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image = JenniferPan.png\n| image_upright = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date =   {{birth date and age|1986|6|17|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]]\n| disappeared_date = \n| disappeared_place = \n| disappeared_status = \n| death_date =     <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| body_discovered = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates =\n| monuments = \n| residence = \n| nationality = [[Canadian]]\n| other_names = \n| citizenship = Canada\n| education = [[Mary Ward Catholic Secondary School]] (did not graduate)\n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = \n| years_active = \n| employer = \n| organization = \n| agent = \n| known_for = \n| notable_works = \n| style = \n| home_town = \n| salary = \n| net_worth = \n| height = \n| weight = \n| television = \n| title = \n| term = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| party = \n| movement = \n| opponents = \n| boards = \n| religion = \n| denomination = \n| criminal_charge = {{ublist|First-degree murder|Attempted murder|Conspiracy to commit murder}}\n| conviction_penalty = [[Life imprisonment]] with possibility of parole after 25 years\n| conviction_status = Incarcerated\n| spouse =         <!-- Do not include unless notable or relevant to the crime involved -->\n| children =       <!-- (as above) -->\n| parents = {{ublist|Huei Hann Pan|Bich Ha Pan}}\n| relatives = Felix Pan\n| callsign = \n| awards = \n| website = \n| allegiance = \n| motive = Romantic relationship, monetary gain, alleged child abuse\n| conviction = \n| reward_amount = \n| capture_status = \n| wanted_by = \n| partners = \n| wanted_since = \n| time_at_large = \n| escaped = \n| escape_end = \n| comments = \n| victims = Bich Ha Pan\n| date = November 8, 2010\n| time = \n| beginyear = \n| endyear = \n| country = Canada\n| states = \n| locations = \n| targets = \n| fatalities = \n| injuries = \n| weapons = \n| apprehended = \n| imprisoned = \n| module =\n| signature =\n| signature_size =\n| signature_alt = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Jennifer Pan''' (born 17 June 1986) is a [[Vietnamese Canadians|Vietnamese-Canadian]] woman of [[Chinese people|Chinese]]-[[Vietnamese people|Vietnamese]] ancestry convicted of a 2010 [[Contract killing|kill-for-hire]] attack targeting both of her parents, in response to their allegedly abusive \"[[tiger parenting]]\" into her mid-20s. The crime took place at the Pan residence in [[Unionville, Ontario|Unionville]], [[Markham, Ontario|Markham]], [[Ontario]], in the [[Greater Toronto Area]]. Jeremy Grimaldi, a journalist of the ''[[Markham Economist & Sun]]'' and the author of ''[[A Daughter's Deadly Deception: The Jennifer Pan Story]]'', stated that the affair \"captivated many, if for nothing else than the sheer intrigue of a case involving [[matricide]], a rarity in Canada.\"<ref name=Grimaldi18years>{{cite news|last=Grimaldi|first=Jeremy|url=https://www.yorkregion.com/news-story/6163269-carty-gets-18-years-for-his-part-in-markham-s-pan-murder/|title=Carty gets 18 years for his part in Markham's Pan murder|work=[[Markham Economist & Sun]]|date=December 7, 2015|accessdate=September 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nJennifer Pan's mother Bich Ha (pronounced \"Bick\"){{#tag:ref|''Bich Ha Pan'': {{zh|first=c,j|c=\u6881\u78a7\u971e|j=loeng4 bik1 haa4|p=Li\u00e1ng B\u00ecxi\u00e1}}<ref name=ZHnameparents>Source of Chinese names: {{cite web|url=http://news.singtao.ca/toronto/content_column_tor.php?IndexID=2863523|title=\u300c\u4e56\u4e56\u5973\u300d\u88ab\u63a7\u5f12\u6bcd.\u842c\u9326\u5165\u5c4b\u52ab\u6bba\u6848\u5cf0\u8ff4\u8def\u8f49|work=[[Sing Tao Daily (Canada)|Sing Tao]]|date=November 24, 2010|accessdate=September 18, 2018}}</ref>|group=note}} and father Huei Hann Pan{{#tag:ref|''Huei Hann Pan'': {{zh|first=t,j||t=\u6f58\u6f22\u8f1d|s=\u6f58\u6c49\u8f89|j=pun1 hon3 fai1|p=P\u0101n H\u00e0nhu\u012b}}<ref name=ZHnameparents/>|group=note}} were Sino-Vietnamese ([[Viet Hoa]]) immigrants to Canada.<ref name=LauImmigrantDream>{{cite news|last1=Lau|first1=Joyce|title=A murder in Toronto and the dark side of the Asian immigrant dream (book review)|url=http://www.scmp.com/magazines/post-magazine/books/article/2043688/murder-toronto-and-dark-side-asian-immigrant-dream|accessdate=9 January 2017|newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]]|date=8 November 2016}}</ref> Hann was born and educated in [[Vietnam]], moving to Canada in 1979 as a [[political refugee]]. Bich also immigrated as a refugee. The couple were married in [[Toronto]] and lived in [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]]. Their two children are Jennifer, born 1986, and Felix, born 1989.<ref name=\"Revenge\">{{cite magazine|last1=Ho|first1=Karen K.|date=22 July 2015|title=Jennifer Pan's Revenge: The inside story of a golden child, the killers she hired, and the parents she wanted dead|url=http://torontolife.com/city/crime/jennifer-pan-revenge/|magazine=[[Toronto Life]]|accessdate=9 January 2017}} - [https://torontolife.com/city/jennifer-pan-revenge-simplified-chinese-translation/ Version in Simplified Chinese]<!--Old URL: http://web.archive.org/web/20150722213215/http://www.torontolife.com/informer/features/2015/07/22/jennifer-pan-revenge-simplified-chinese-translation/--></ref><ref name=WangGoldenDaughter>{{cite news|last1=Wang|first1=Yanan|title=Tragedy of 'golden' daughter's fall resonates with Asian immigrant children|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/07/27/tragedy-of-golden-daughters-murder-plot-against-parents-resonates-with-asian-immigrant-children/|accessdate=9 January 2017|newspaper=[[Washington Post]]|date=27 July 2015}}</ref> \n\nThe Pans found work at [[Magna International]], an auto parts manufacturer in [[Aurora, Ontario|Aurora]], [[Ontario]].<ref name=Revenge/> Hann worked as a tool and die maker, while Bich made car parts. The couple persistently worked hard for their money to ensure that their children had the upbringing and opportunities they themselves had missed out on. Hann and Bich were thrifty and by 2004 were financially stable enough to purchase a \"large\" house with a two-car garage on a residential street in [[Markham, Ontario|Markham]], a town with a large Asian population.<ref name=LauImmigrantDream/> Bich drove a [[Lexus ES 300]] and Hann drove a [[Mercedes-Benz C-Class (W203)]]. They had accumulated [[Canadian dollar|CAD$]]200,000 in savings.<ref name=Revenge/>\n\nJennifer's parents set many goals for their children and had extremely high expectations of them. Jennifer was made to take piano lessons at the age of four, as well as [[figure skating]] classes where she trained most days during the week. She had hopes of becoming an [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] figure skating champion until she tore a ligament in her knee. Jennifer attended [[Mary Ward Catholic Secondary School]] where she played the [[flute]] in the school band.<ref name=Revenge/> According to her high school friend Karen K. Ho, Hann was seen as \"the classic [[tiger parenting|tiger dad]],\" and Bich was \"his reluctant accomplice.\" The Pans picked Jennifer up when classes ended each day and monitored her extracurricular activities very closely. They never permitted her to date boys while attending high school, or to attend high school dances or [[prom]]s out of fear that these activities would distract her from her academic commitments. Jennifer was not permitted to attend any parties while her parents believed that she was attending university. At the age of 22, \"she had never gone to a club, been drunk, visited a friend's cottage or gone on vacation without her family.\"<ref name=Revenge/> Jennifer and her friends reportedly regarded this upbringing as restrictive and greatly oppressive.<ref name=Revenge/>\n\nDespite her parents' high expectations and the fact that Jennifer had received good grades in lower school, throughout high school her grades were somewhat average (in the 70% range) except for music. Multiple times, she forged [[report card]]s using false templates to show her parents that she had received straight As when she had not. When Jennifer failed calculus class in her senior year of high school, [[Ryerson University]] rescinded her early admission. As she could not bear to be perceived as a failure, she began to lie to those she knew, including her parents, and pretended she was attending university. Instead, she sat in caf\u00e9s, taught as a piano instructor and worked in a restaurant to earn money. In order to maintain the charade, Jennifer told her parents she had won scholarships, later falsely claiming that she had accepted an offer into the pharmacology program at the [[University of Toronto]]. She went to the extent of purchasing second-hand textbooks and watching videos related to pharmacology in order to create notebooks full of purported class notes that she could show her parents. Jennifer also requested permission from her parents to stay near the campus with a friend throughout the week.<ref name=Revenge/>\n\nJennifer was actually staying with her boyfriend,<ref name=Revenge/> Daniel Chi-Kwong Wong,{{#tag:ref|''Daniel Chi-Kwong Wong'': {{zh|first=t,j|t=\u9ec3\u5fd7\u5149|s=\u9ec4\u5fd7\u5149|j=wong4 zi3 gwong1|p=Hu\u00e1ng Zh\u00ecgu\u0101ng|labels=no}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.singtao.ca/toronto/2014-05-10/city1399706077d5044769.html|title=\u7537\u53cb\u7206\u6f58\u5973\u66fe\u906d5\u6f22\u6027\u4fb5 \u8072\u7a31\u6536\u8b66\u544a\u77ed\u8a0a \u77e2\u53e3\u5426\u8a8d\u6d89\u6848|work=[[Sing Tao Daily]]|date=2014-05-10|accessdate=2018-09-18}}</ref>|group=note}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/4th-arrest-in-markham-home-invasion-homicide-1.1038532|agency=[[The Canadian Press]]|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]]|title=4th arrest in Markham home invasion homicide|date=2011-04-26|accessdate=2018-09-18}}</ref> a high school sweetheart whom her parents knew nothing about.<ref name=Revenge/><ref name=\"BrownChineseCubs\">{{cite news|last1=Brown|first1=Vanessa|title=When Chinese cubs turn on their Tiger Parents|url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/real-life/true-stories/when-chinese-cubs-turn-on-their-tiger-parents/news-story/36ad884522b2d22ba1e2f88faa5d72ab|accessdate=9 January 2017|work=News.com.au|date=11 December 2016}}</ref><ref>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.com/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT31 PT 31]: \"[...]commenting on the fact that he was only half Chinese. \"[...]you're [part] Filipino.\"\"</ref> Wong was of mixed Chinese and [[Filipino people|Filipino]] ancestry,<ref name=\"BrownChineseCubs\">{{cite news|last1=Brown|first1=Vanessa|title=When Chinese cubs turn on their Tiger Parents|url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/real-life/true-stories/when-chinese-cubs-turn-on-their-tiger-parents/news-story/36ad884522b2d22ba1e2f88faa5d72ab|accessdate=9 January 2017|work=News.com.au|date=11 December 2016}}</ref><ref>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.es/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT31 PT 31]: \"[...]commenting on the fact that he was only half Chinese. \"[...]you're [part] Filipino.\"\"</ref> resided in [[Ajax, Ontario|Ajax]],<ref name=GillisWendyFifth>{{cite news|author=Gillis, Wendy|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/crime/2011/05/04/fifth_suspect_arrested_in_deadly_markham_home_invasion.html|title=Fifth suspect arrested in deadly Markham home invasion |newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=May 4, 2011|accessdate=September 18, 2018}}</ref> and worked at a [[Boston Pizza]] restaurant.<ref name=GrimaldiPT90>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [https://books.google.cz/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT90 PT 90]. \"Daniel Wong is arrested at work in front of his colleagues at Boston Pizza on April 26, 2011.\"</ref> Wong, once a student at Mary Ward, transferred to [[Cardinal Carter Academy]] in North York, Toronto due to low grades<!--\"he was falling behind\"-->, and later studied at [[York University]].<ref name=Revenge/> He was an active marijuana dealer.<ref name=Revenge/><!--\"he had been charged with trafficking after cops found half a pound of weed in his car.\"--><ref name=Dimannoastonishing>{{cite news|last=Dimanno|first=Rosie|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/crime/2014/09/15/the_fantastic_testimony_of_jennifer_pan.html|title=The astonishing testimony of Jennifer Pan|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=September 15, 2014|accessdate=September 25, 2018|quote=Seven years until Wong \u2014 Pan says he was the one who put her in touch with \u201cHomeboy,\u201d a man he knew through his marijuana dealing}}</ref>\n\n==Adult life==\nWhile pretending to complete her degree at the University of Toronto, Pan told her parents that she had started working as a volunteer at Toronto's [[The Hospital for Sick Children, Toronto|Hospital for Sick Children]], known as Sick Kids. Hann and Bich soon became suspicious when they realized she did not have a hospital ID badge or uniform. On one occasion, Bich followed her daughter to \"work\" and quickly discovered her deception. In a state of shock, Hann wanted to throw Jennifer out of the house, but her mother persuaded him to allow her to stay. As she had not completed high school due to failing [[calculus]], she eventually began working to finish high school completely and was later encouraged by her parents to apply to university. She was, however, forbidden to contact Wong or to go anywhere except to her piano-teaching job. Nevertheless, she and Wong spoke clandestinely during this period.<ref name=Revenge/>\n\nBy the time that Jennifer was 24, Wong had grown weary of trying to pursue a relationship with her. As Jennifer was so daunted and restricted by her parents that she lived at home and only met him in secret, Wong began to date another young woman whom he soon fell in love with.<ref name=Revenge/> Pan quickly invented a new story and told Wong that a man had entered her house, showing what appeared to be a police badge. She then told him that several men had rushed in and [[gang-rape]]d her. After this, she insisted that a bullet was mailed to her, telling Wong that it was sent from his new girlfriend.<ref name=Revenge/>\n\n==Murder==\nIn Spring 2010, Pan was in contact with Andrew Montemayor, a high school friend who, she claims, had boasted in their high school years about robbing people at knife point, an assertion denied by Montemayor. Montemayor introduced her to Ricardo Duncan, a \"[[Goth subculture|goth]] kid\" whom Pan gave $1,500 to kill her father in the parking lot at his workplace. Duncan says that she once gave him $200 for a night out, but that he returned it, and that he rebuffed her when she asked him to kill her parents.<ref name=Revenge/>\n\nPan and Wong were back in contact at this time and according to the police, came up with a plan to hire a professional [[hitman]] for $10,000 to kill her parents, calculating that she would then inherit $500,000. They planned to move in together. Wong connected Pan with a man,<ref name=Revenge/> Lenford Roy Crawford,<ref name=GillisWendyFifth/> Jamaican-born,<ref>Grimaldi, ''[[A Daughter's Deadly Deception]]'', {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA81 81].</ref> whom he called Homeboy, and gave her a [[SIM card]] and an [[iPhone]] so that she could contact Crawford without using her usual cell phone.<ref name=Revenge/> Crawford contacted another man,<ref name=HashamCrownfinishpres>{{cite news|last=Hasham|first=Alyshah|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/crime/2014/08/13/crown_finishes_presenting_evidence_against_jennifer_pan_in_murder_trial.html|title=Crown finishes presenting evidence against Jennifer Pan in murder trial|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=August 13, 2014|accessdate=September 20, 2018|quote=[...]who in turn involved David Mylvaganam, allegedly one of three men who[...]It remains unclear who the other two men who entered the house are. The jury has heard that Crawford and Wong were both at work at the time of the murder. }}</ref> named Eric Shawn \"Sniper\" Carty,<ref name=GrimaldiCartydead>{{cite web|last=Grimaldi|first=Jeremy|url=https://www.yorkregion.com/news-story/8680927-eric-carty-linchpin-in-jennifer-pan-murder-plot-dies-in-jail/|title=Eric Carty, linchpin in Jennifer Pan murder plot, dies in jail|work=[[Markham Economist & Sun]]|date=2018-06-26|accessdate=2018-09-29}}</ref> who in turn contacted Montreal-born David Mylvaganam.<ref name=HashamCrownfinishpres/><ref name=\"LauImmigrantDream\" /> Crawford lived in [[Brampton, Ontario|Brampton]] and Mylvaganam lived in Toronto, while Carty,<ref name=GillisWendyFifth/> who previously lived in [[Rexdale, Toronto]],<ref name=GrimaldiCartydead/> at the time did not have a fixed residence.<ref name=GillisWendyFifth/> The Crown (Canadian government) stated that Mylvaganam was one of the hitmen.<ref name=HashamCrownfinishpres/> Carty was later found responsible for an unrelated murder, and Grimaldi stated that Carty was \"a repeat violent offender\".<ref name=Grimaldi18years/>\n\nThe murder took place at the Pan house in [[Unionville, Ontario|Unionville]], in [[Markham, Ontario|Markham]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/4431797-markham-murder-trial-resumes-with-father-still-on-stand/|title=Markham murder trial resumes with father still on stand|agency=[[Markham Economist & Sun]]|work=[[Guelph Mercury Tribune]]|date=March 26, 2014|accessdate=September 19, 2018|quote=[...]in Unionville in this file photograph. This was the scene of the murder of Bich Pan in 2010.}}</ref> On November 8, 2010, Pan unlocked the front door of the family home when she went to bed, then spoke by phone to Mylvaganam. Shortly afterwards, Mylvaganam and two other people entered the home through the unlocked front door, all carrying guns.<ref name=Revenge/> In the court testimony, the Crown did not establish the identity of the other two hitmen; Wong and Crawford were at work.<ref name=HashamCrownfinishpres/> Carty stated that he was the driver for those who broke into the house, and that he selected them and was involved in plotting the attack. He did not state that he was one of the three or that he directly attacked others.<ref name=Grimaldi18years/> Grimaldi stated that the identity of the triggerperson remains unknown.<ref name=Grimaldi18years/><!--\"To this day, it remains unclear who pulled the trigger,[...]\"-->\n\nAfter demanding all the money in the house and ransacking the main bedroom, the three men took Bich and Hann to the basement where they shot them multiple times. Bich was killed but Hann would survive his wounds. The three men then took all the cash that was in the house including $2,000 from Pan and left. Pan claimed that they tied her up, but that she managed to free her hands and dial [[9-1-1]].<ref name=Revenge/> Hann Pan was treated at [[Markham Stouffville Hospital]],<ref name=Grimaldip17alone>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA17 17].</ref> before being moved to a trauma unit<ref name=Grimaldip27alone>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA27 27].</ref> at [[Sunnybrook Hospital]] in [[Toronto]],<ref name=Grimaldip35alone>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA35 35].</ref> by aircraft.<ref name=Grimaldip27alone/>\n\n== Investigation and arrests ==\nThe evening after the murder, Pan underwent her first interview with the police.<ref name=Grimaldip18alone>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA18 18].</ref> Pan was arrested on November 22, 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/jennifer-pan-plotted-to-have-parents-killed-says-crown-1.2579135|title=Jennifer Pan plotted to have parents killed, says Crown|agency=[[The Canadian Press]]|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]]|date=March 19, 2014|accessdate=September 18, 2018}}</ref> during her third interview at the Markham police station (5 District) of [[York Regional Police]].<ref name=Grimaldiinterviewarrest>Grimaldi - Interview date: {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA66 66]. \"During her third police interview, on November 22, 2016, Jennifer opens up to Detective Goetz[...]\" - Arrest: {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA74 74]. Also {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.cz/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT273 PT 273]. \"[...]Goetz returns before calmly stating, \"[...]At this point of the investigation I will be arresting you for murder,[...]\"\"</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Grimaldi, Jeremy|url=https://www.durhamregion.com/news-story/4489558-jennifer-pan-betrays-her-own-web-of-lies-in-videotaped-interview/|title=Jennifer Pan betrays her own 'web of lies' in videotaped interview|website=[[DurhamRegion.com]]|date=2014-04-29|accessdate=2018-09-23|quote=Ms Pan\u2019s dramatic admission came after more than two hours of questioning in a small windowless room at York Police\u2019s markham station}}</ref> During that interview Pan admitted that she hired killers, but stated that she hired them to kill her.<ref name=GrimaldiIthought>{{cite web|last=Grimaldi|first=Jeremy|url=https://www.yorkregion.com/news-story/4490794--i-thought-you-were-on-my-side-pan-tells-york-police/|title='I thought you were on my side', Pan tells York Police|work=[[Markham Economist & Sun]]|date=April 29, 2014|accessdate=September 22, 2018}}</ref> The interrogating police officer, William \"Bill\" Goetz,<ref name=Revenge/><!--for William--><ref name=GrimaldiIthought/><!--for Bill--> falsely told Pan that he had computer software that could analyze untruths in statements and that there were satellites that used [[infrared]] technology to analyze movements in buildings;<ref name=GrimaldiIthought/> in Canada police are legally allowed to lie to those they are interrogating in regards to the evidence in the trial,<ref name=GrimaldiPT62>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.com/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT62 PT 62]. \"Police in Canada might be allowed to lie to suspects about the evidence they have collected,[...]\"</ref> as well as in regards to the strategies they are using.<ref>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.com/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT50 PT50]. \"In 2000, the Supreme Court of Canada ruled that police are allowed to lie not only about evidence but tactics, as well.\"</ref> Goetz had used the [[Reid technique]] to ensnare Pan.<ref>{{cite news|last=Grimaldi|first=Jeremy|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/insight/2016/11/13/youre-a-good-person-thats-made-a-mistake-here.html|title=The story behind the confession of Jennifer Pan |newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=November 13, 2016}} - An excerpt of the book ''[[A Daughter's Deadly Deception]]''.</ref>\n\nMylvaganam was arrested at the [[Jane Finch Mall]] in [[North York, Toronto]] on April 14, 2011. Carty was arrested at the prison he was held in, [[Maplehurst Correctional Complex]] in [[Milton, Ontario]], on April 15, 2011.<ref>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [https://books.google.com/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT89 PT89]. \"Two days after speaking with Denise Brown, Detective Courtice gives the order to take David down.[...]The following day, police descend on Maplehurst Correctional[...]where Eric Carty is held, and charge him with the same.\" [https://books.google.com/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT88 PT88] states: \"[...]on April 12, when police finally get in touch with Denise Brown,[...]\"</ref> Wong was arrested on April 26, 2011 at his place of employment.<ref name=GrimaldiPT90/> Crawford was the final suspect arrested, entering custody on May 4, 2011 in Brampton.<ref>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA109 109]. Also: {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [https://books.google.cz/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT91 PT 91]. \"Lenford is arrested on May 4[...]Brampton driveway.[...]no further charges are laid in his case.\"</ref>\n\n==Trial==\nThe trial of Pan and her accomplices began on March 19, 2014 in [[Newmarket, Ontario|Newmarket]] and continued for ten months. All pleaded not guilty to the charges of [[Murder|first degree murder]], [[attempted murder]], and [[Conspiracy to murder|conspiracy to commit murder]]. At the trial, [[York Regional Police]] evidence included exhaustive tracking of the mobile device movements and text message traffic, including over 100 messages sent between Pan and Wong in the six hours prior to the killing.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://casefilepodcast.com/case-50-jennifer-pan/|title=Case 50: Jennifer Pan - Casefile: True Crime Podcast|date=2017-04-16|work=Casefile: True Crime Podcast|access-date=2018-02-13|language=en-US}}</ref> Further evidence centered around the atypical nature of the \"break-in\", \"robbery\", shootings, and irregularities in Pan's testimony. Pan's obsession with Wong, her lack of true emotion and a confession regarding the attack, and recognition of the [[Tiger mother|trauma she underwent]] were also detailed.<ref name=\":0\" /> A major irregularity was that Pan was not assaulted, blindfolded, taken to the basement, nor shot, leaving behind an eyewitness to the attack. Evidence from Hann, which differed greatly from Pan's version, also undermined her credibility, as did her inability to recreate the conditions of her 9-1-1 call when her hands were bound behind her (given that the police were the ones who had actually cut the shoelace to release her).<ref name=\":0\" /> The trial included over 200 exhibits; over 50 witnesses testified at the trial.<ref name=Revenge/>\n\nPan, Wong, Mylvaganam and Crawford were all convicted on December 13, 2014, and each received a life sentence with no chance of parole for 25 years.<ref name=\"Revenge\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/toronto/jennifer-pan-toronto-woman-whose-plot-to-kill-parents-left-mother-dead-gets-life-in-prison|title=Jennifer Pan, Toronto woman whose plot to kill parents left mother dead, gets life in prison|author=Paola Loriggio, The Canadian Press|date=24 January 2015|work=National Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/jennifer-pan-sentenced-to-life-without-parole-for-25-years-1.2930113|title=Jennifer Pan sentenced to life without parole for 25 years|date=23 January 2015|work=cbc.ca}}</ref><ref name=GrimaldiLifesent>{{cite news|author=Grimaldi, Jeremy|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2015/01/23/convicted-mother-killer-jennifer-pan-hears-sentence.html|title=Jennifer Pan: Life with no parole for 25 years in murder of mother, attempted murder of father|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=23 January 2015|quote=[...]including a non-communication request from Hann Pan, Felix Pan and other family members, banning Pan from contacting any of them.[...]But Justice Crawford disregarded this and went ahead with the ban.}}</ref>\n\nOriginally Carty was tried with the other perpetrators. [[Edward Sapiano]], Carty's lawyer fell ill,<ref name=Dimannoastonishing/> so around the Summer of 2014<!--\"mid-2014\"--> his case was declared a mistrial. In December 2015, Carty received an 18-year sentence after pleading guilty to conspiring to commit murder. He was to be eligible for parole after nine years. According to Carty, he did not wish to subject Hann Pan to another criminal trial<!--\"[...]said he wanted to put an end to Hann's suffering by pleading out to avoid another lengthy trial.\"-->.<ref name=Grimaldi18years/>\n\n===Penalties and imprisonment===\nJennifer Pan was sentenced to life with no parole for 25 years for the murder of her mother, and attempted murder of her father. Pan's father and brother requested a court order that banned Jennifer Pan from contacting members of her surviving family. Despite the objections of the defense lawyers, the judge filed the order.<ref name=GrimaldiLifesent/> Pan is also barred from contacting Wong.<ref name=Grimaldip314alone>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA314 314].</ref>\n\n{{Asof|2016}} Pan was serving her sentence at the [[Grand Valley Institution for Women]] in [[Kitchener, Ontario]].<ref name=Grimaldip313andPT273>Grimaldi, 1459735250, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA313 313], or {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262 [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.cz/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT273 PT273].</ref> Wong, previously held in [[Lindsay, Ontario]], was at [[Collins Bay Institution]] in [[Kingston, Ontario]]. Mylvaganam was at [[Atlantic Institution]] in [[Renous, New Brunswick]].<ref name=Grimaldip312alone>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA312 312].</ref> Crawford was at [[Kent Institution]] in [[Agassiz, British Columbia]].<ref name=Grimaldip313alone>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA313 313].</ref> Carty, who requested to go to a federal prison in Western Canada or Atlantic Canada, was still at the provincial [[Millhaven Assessment Unit]], awaiting his transfer to a federal prison.<ref name=Grimaldip313andPT273/> Carty, who later moved to Kent, died in his cell on April 26, 2018.<ref name=GrimaldiCartydead/>\n\n==Media reaction==\nAccording to the ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', the case \"sent shockwaves across Canada and the Asian [[diaspora]].\"<ref name=\"LauImmigrantDream\" /> An editorial in the ''[[Northwest Asian Weekly]]'' suggested consideration of the \"idea of recognizing the mental and psychological symptoms that parenting may have gone too far\" in the Pan household.<ref name=\"LoveHate\">{{cite news|last1=Editorial|title=Is it possible to love and hate?|url=http://nwasianweekly.com/2015/08/editorial-is-it-possible-to-love-and-hate-the-strange-case-of-jennifer-pan/|accessdate=9 January 2017|work=[[Northwest Asian Weekly]]|date=15 August 2015}} - [https://search.proquest.com/docview/1706574280 Also at] [[ProQuest]]</ref> A story by Karen K. Ho in ''[[Toronto Life]]'' magazine brought the story to widespread attention by framing it an instance of tiger parenting gone tragically wrong.<ref name=\"Revenge\" /><ref name=\"WangGoldenDaughter\" /><ref name=\"LoveHate\" /> In 2016, journalist Jeremy Grimaldi published a [[true crime]] book about Pan called ''[[A Daughter's Deadly Deception|A Daughter's Deadly Deception: The Jennifer Pan Story]]''.<ref name=\"LauImmigrantDream\" /><ref name=\"BrownChineseCubs\"/> The ''[[Casefile True Crime Podcast|Casefile]]'' and ''[[My Favorite Murder]]'' [[podcasts]] and the ''[[Deadly Women]]'' series also covered the case.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Aftermath==\nBich-Ha Pan's funeral was held on November 15, 2010 and took place at the Ogden Chapel in Scarborough. A funeral for Bich Ha's father was held prior to satisfy a Vietnamese custom that asks for older members of the family to have their funerals first. Jennifer Pan had organized both funerals and had been asked to do so.<!--\"[...]something she later complains her father left her to organize all by herself.\"--><ref>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.cz/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT49 PT49].</ref> Bich-Ha was buried on November 19.<!--\"Three days after burying her mother, on November 22, Jennifer receives a phone call[...]she has to come in again to speak with the police.\"--><ref>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.cz/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT50 PT50].</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bart Whitaker]] \u2013 A Texas man who ordered a hit on his family after he faked continuing attending a university<!--He had dropped out: https://www.cbsnews.com/news/bart-whitaker-execution-reprieve-greg-abbott/ \"Unknown to his parents, the dinner celebration marking his graduation was a fraud. He'd dropped out of school months earlier.\" -->\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n* Grimaldi, Jeremy. ''[[A Daughter's Deadly Deception: The Jennifer Pan Story]]''. [[Dundurn Books]], November 12, 2016.\n** {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262.\n** {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255.\n\n=== Reference notes ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.yorkregion.com/yorkregion-topics/4420090-pan-murder-trial/ Index of articles] - ''[[Yorkregion.com]]''\n* [http://casefilepodcast.com/case-49-moors-murders-part-2/ Casefile True Crime Podcast - Case 50: Jennifer Pan] - 15 April 2017\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pan, Jennifer}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Markham, Ontario]]\n[[Category:People from Toronto]]\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Hoa descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:Matricides]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment by Canada]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian criminals]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of Canada]]\n[[Category:Canadian female criminals]]\n[[Category:Canadian female murderers]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by Canada]]\n", "name_user": "SebastianDrawsStuff", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life and education", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jennifer_Pan"}
{"title_page": "Annapurna Circuit", "text_new": "{{Undisclosed paid|date=February 2020}}\n[[File:Under stars and snows.jpg|350px|thumb|View of [[Machapuchare|Mt. Machapuchare]] from Annapurna Base Camp]]\nThe '''Annapurna Circuit''' is a [[trekking|trek]] within the mountain ranges of central [[Nepal]]. The total length of the route varies between 160\u2013230&nbsp;km (100-145&nbsp;mi), depending on where motor transportation is used and where the trek is ended. This trek crosses two different river valleys and encircles the [[Annapurna Massif]]. The path reaches its highest point at [[Thorung La]] pass (5416m/17769&nbsp;ft), touching the edge of the [[Tibetan plateau]]. Practically all trekkers hike the route anticlockwise, as this way the daily altitude gain is slower, and crossing the high Thorong La pass is easier and safer.\n\nIn addition to the Annapurna Circuit Trek, Annapurna Seven Passes Trek or Annapurna Seven Hills trek is also popular in the region. However, this is less traversed and is off the beaten path trek in the region.   \n\nThe mountain scenery, seen at close quarters includes the Annapurna Massif (Annapurna I-IV), [[Dhaulagiri]], [[Machhapuchhre]], [[Manaslu]], [[Gangapurna]], [[Tilicho Peak]], [[Pisang Peak]], and [[Paungda Danda]].  Numerous other peaks of 6000-8000m in elevation rise from the Annapurna range.\n\nThe trek begins at [[Besisahar]] or Bhulbhule in the [[Marshyangdi]] river valley and concludes in the [[Kali Gandaki Gorge]]. Besisahar can be reached after a seven-hour drive from [[Kathmandu]].  The trail passes along paddy fields and into subtropical forests, several waterfalls and gigantic cliffs, and various villages. \n\nAnnapurna Circuit has often been voted as the best long-distance trek in the world, as it combined, in its old full form, a wide variety of climate zones from tropics at 600 m asl to the arctic at 5416 m asl at the Thorong La pass and cultural variety from Hindu villages at the low foothills to the Tibetan culture of Manang Valley and lower Mustang. Continuing construction of a road has shortened the trail and changed the villages. The Beisahar-Manag road has been built which passes through the trekking trail most of the time.  With construction of the road, mountain biking is becoming popular, with Mustang in particular becoming one of the world's most popular mountain biking destinations.\n\n== Standard trek duration ==\n{{wide image|Annapurna Massif Panorama.jpg|990px|View of Annapurna massif near [[Manang]], [[Nepal]].}}\nThe [https://www.mantraadventure.com/trip/annapurna-circuit-trek/ Annapurna Base Circuit trek] usually takes about 15\u201320 days,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.alienadv.com/faq/10/Annapurna-Circuit-Trek/|title=Annapurna Circuit Trek|access-date=2016-08-23}}</ref> leaving from Kathmandu with a stopover in [[Pokhara]] before returning to the capital.<ref name=\":0\" /> The trail is moderate to fairly challenging and makes numerous river crossings over steel and wooden [[suspension bridge]]s. Tea houses and lodges along the circuit are available for meals and accommodations. Some groups may opt for tents but these are typically only used for side trips away from lodges such as climbing a peak.<ref name=\":0\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wanderingsasquatch.com/how-to-hike-the-annapurna-circuit/|title=How to Hike the Annapurna Circuit|date=2013-06-13|language=en-US|access-date=2016-08-23}}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}}\n\n'''Outline Itinerary'''\n[[File:Marsyangdi river valley near Pisang.jpg|thumb|right|350px|[[Paungda Danda]] and Marsyangdi river valley near [[Pisang]]]]\nDay 01 - From Kathmandu, travel west to [[Besisahar]] [820m/2690&nbsp;ft] via private vehicle or public bus, taking six to seven hours.\n\nDay 02 - Trek to [[Khudi, Nepal|Khudi]] [790m/2592&nbsp;ft]\n\nDay 03 - Trek to [[Bahundanda]] [1310m/4298&nbsp;ft]\n\nDay 04 - Trek to [[Jagat, Nepal|Jagat]] [1290m/4232&nbsp;ft]\n\nDay 05 - Trek to [[Dharapani, Gandaki|Dharapani]] [1920m/6299&nbsp;ft]\n\nDay 06 - Trek to [[Chame, Nepal|Chame]] [2630m/8629&nbsp;ft]\n\nDay 07 - Trek to Upper/Lower [[Pisang]] [3190m/10466&nbsp;ft]\n\nDay 08 - Trek to [[Manang]] [3520m/11549&nbsp;ft]\n\nDay 09 - Rest day in Manang [3520m/11549&nbsp;ft]\n\nDay 10 - Trek to [[Letdar]] [4250m/13944&nbsp;ft]\n\nDay 11 - Trek to [[Thorung Phedi]] [4500m/14764&nbsp;ft]\n\nDay 12 - Trek to [[Muktinath]] [3800m/12467&nbsp;ft], crossing the [[Thorung La]] en route\n\nDay 13 - Trek to [[Marpha]] [2665m/8743&nbsp;ft]\n\nDay 14 - Trek to [[Lete, Nepal|Lete]] [2470m/8104&nbsp;ft] (now often with car or mountainbike)\n\nDay 15 - Trek to [[Tatopani, Myagdi|Tatopani]] [1160m/3806&nbsp;ft] (now often with car or mountainbike, day 14)\n\nDay 16 - Trek to [[Ghorepani]] [2775m/9104&nbsp;ft]\n\nDay 17 - Trek to [[Birethanti]] [1050m/3445&nbsp;ft] and travel to [[Pokhara]]\n\nDay 18 - Return to Kathmandu [1400m/4593&nbsp;ft]\n<ref>see more itinerary</ref>\nDepending on the speed of the trekkers, number and length of side trips and rest days taken, acclimatization, weather and where the trek is finished, hiking the Annapurna Circuit can take anything from 8 to 25 days. Many trekkers short on time choose to fly out from [[Jomsom Airport]], which shortens the trek by 6 days compared to the original AC.\n\nIt is also possible to continue from Ghorepani to Tadapani, [[Ghandruk]], Landruk and then to Phedi, which follows the old Annapurna Circuit from the time when the road was not yet extended to Beni. This more faithful variation takes three days instead of the shorter one-day exit from Ghorepani to Pokhara outlined above. A popular addition to the AC is a visit to Annapurna Base Camp, ABC (also called [[Annapurna Sanctuary]]). This trail turns to the north from Tadapani and rejoins the old AC at either Ghandruk or Landruk. A visit to the ABC adds about 5 days to the duration of the Annapurna Circuit, slightly less than the normal trek duration to ABC, as trekkers coming from the AC are already acclimatized and \"trail hardened\".\n\nIt is recommended that trekkers take the high trail from [[Pisang]] via [[Ghyaru]] and Ngawal to Manang, as the views are spectacular and the two villages along the route are some of the best preserved samples of Tibetan style villages still in their original state. Sleeping in either of these villages assists with acclimatization, as they are located already higher than Manang. Another side trip gaining popularity is the visit to [[Tilicho Lake|Tilicho Tal]], a lake. There are now lodges along the trail and near the lake at so-called Tilicho Base Camp, so tents are no longer required. If one wishes to cross to Jomsom via the Tilicho route, outdoor camping (and thus a tent) is required.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nepal-dia.de/int__England/EV_Annapurna/EB_Tilicho/eb_tilicho.html|title=Tilicho- Trekking in Nepal Annapurna|website=www.nepal-dia.de|access-date=2016-08-23}}</ref> At certain times of year, snow conditions can make the crossing dangerous or prevent it altogether.\n\nIn October 2014, Seth Wolpin achieved the fastest known time in 72 hours and 4 minutes. He started in Besisahar and finished in Naya Pull, following all New Annapurna Trekking Trails.<ref>http://sethwolpin.com/2014/10/the-annapurna-circuit-going-round-and.html/</ref><ref>http://trailrunningnepal.org/annapurna-circuit-trek-fastest-known-time-fkt/</ref>\n\nIt is reported<ref>http://trailrunningnepal.org/new-annapurna-circuit-fastest-known-time-fkt/</ref> that time has been recently surpassed by Greek athlete and philanthropist Lefteris Paraskevas, who, in May 2017 completed the classic route of the Circuit, from Besisahar to Nayapulin, in 68 hours and 22 minutes.\n\n== Annapurna circuit weather ==\nWhile much of the Himalayas cannot be trekked in the wet season, much of the Annapurna circuit actually sits within a [[rain shadow]]. This means that it is possible to trek most parts of the circuit all year-round, including the monsoon period.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nTrekking in the wet season is often encouraged as hikers avoid the crowds that plague the summer months. However, the days are often damp and many of the views are obscured by cloud.\n\n=== October \u2013 November ===\nThis is the most popular hiking season in Nepal. Due to the recent monsoons, everything along the circuit is refreshed, clean and vibrant. Views are usually clear and the night sky is extremely visible. Though the weather is generally warm, nighttime temperatures drop below freezing. This is the busiest period on the circuit and tea houses book up very quickly.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Best time to trek the Annapurna Circuit - Kandoo Adventures|url = http://www.trekkinginnepal.org/annapurna-circuit-weather/|website = Kandoo Adventures|access-date = 2016-01-19|language = en-gb|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160126171358/http://www.trekkinginnepal.org/annapurna-circuit-weather/|archive-date = 2016-01-26|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\n=== December \u2013 March ===\nThis is the coldest period on the circuit. Depending on the altitude, day time temperatures will be cold and night time temperatures drop well below freezing. The trade off is that the trails are much less busy. Thorung La Pass, which stands at over 5,400 meters, is often blocked with snow and may be closed for days on end. Unless the snow blocks most trails, tea houses still remain open during this period. Clouds prevail more frequently, but clear days are still common. Towards March the rhododendrons start flowering, which brings hill sides alive with flaming colours. Unfortunately, this period is also when avalanches are most common. Completing the circuit might be possible during December but from January onward it becomes quite challenging and should be avoided unless advised by the locals.\n\n=== April \u2013 May ===\nBecause of the warming weather, April to May is the second most popular trekking season on the Annapurna Circuit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://trailblazer-guides.com/book/trekking-in-the-annapurna-region/when-to-go|title=Trailblazer Guide Books|website=trailblazer-guides.com|access-date=2016-08-23}}</ref> Most of the snow has dissipated, leaving crystal clear skies. There is often a strange haze that can be seen from the lower altitudes during May. However, this soon passes and cannot be seen from higher up the trail. As the monsoon period builds towards the end of May, the days become hotter and more humid which makes trekking at lower altitude quite uncomfortable.\n\n=== June \u2013 September ===\nThis is the monsoon period. Although there are stories of torrential downpours, mudslides and hordes of leeches, this is rarely the case on the Annapurna Circuit, particular the northern section. Whilst the south section of the Annapurna Circuit near Pokhara does get a lot of rain, the northern parts often receive less than 10% of the precipitation due to the location within a [[rain shadow]]. The upside of trekking in the monsoon period is that many of the flora species flower during this period, making the trek exceptionally beautiful. This is also the time when the Tilicho Lake side trek is relatively easier.\n\n== History ==\n\nThe Annapurna area was opened to foreign trekkers in 1977 after the disputes between CIA backed [[Kham]]pa guerrillas operating from the area into Tibet, and the local populace and Nepal army were settled. The original trek started from the market town of Dhumre situated at the Kathmandu - Pokhara highway and ended in Pokhara, and took about 23 days to complete. Road construction started in early 1980s both from Dhumre to the north and from Pokhara to the west and then up the Kali Gandaki valley. The road has now reached Chamje on the [[Marsyangdi]] river valley and Muktinath on the Kali Gandaki side. Of the trek's original 23 days, only 5 walking days of the trek are now without a motor road. In places new trails and routes have been marked so that the road can be partly avoided. The existence of the road has nevertheless changed the area, appearance, and atmosphere of the villages. The road facilitates transport, increasing the popularity of mountain biking in the area. Since 2011, companies in Muktinath and Jomsom rent out mountain bikes to tourists. As the road sees very little traffic, and one can ride downhill (dirt road and/or single track) from Muktinath to Tatopani and descend almost 3000 meters in 2\u20133 days.\n\nNew areas near Annapurna have been opened for trekkers in the past years, such as Upper Mustang, Naar-Pho Valley, Manaslu and Tsum Valley. Currently, trekking these areas is restricted and subject to extra permits, costs, and other limitations.\n\n==2014 blizzard==\n{{main article|2014 Nepal snowstorm disaster}}\nIn October 2014, a sudden [[blizzard]] killed over 43 people, half of whom were Nepalese.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/oct/16/nepal-blizzard-survivor-deaths-annapurna-refuge Annapurna blizzard]</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/21/world/asia/nepal-tragedy-reverberates-across-borders.html?hp&action=click&pgtype=Homepage&version=HpSumSmallMediaHigh&module=second-column-region&region=top-news&WT.nav=top-news&_r=0 Nepalese tragedy]</ref>  It was caused by the tail end of a dying cyclone which had ravaged the eastern coast of India; there were about 350 hikers caught in the blizzard.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/17/world/asia/hikers-blizzard-nepal.html?hp&action=click&pgtype=Homepage&version=HpSum&module=second-column-region&region=top-news&WT.nav=top-news Hikers caught in blizzard]</ref>\n\n== Communications ==\nMultiple locations of the trek circuit now have an Internet connection. This multi-district circuit's trekkers can use wireless internet across different districts like in Kaski, Myagdi, Lamjung and Mustang. Cellular 3G is also available at some locations.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Annapurna trekking circuit villages get Wi-Fi Internet \u2022 TechSansar.com|url = http://techsansar.com/tech-news/annapurna-trekking-circuit-wifi-internet/|website = |publisher = |accessdate = 2015-12-06|language = en-US}}</ref>{{coord|28.794671|N|83.937368|E|dim:80000_region:NP-GA_type:mountain_source:dewiki|display=title}}\n\n==Annapurna circuit trek gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Thorong-trail.jpg | On the way to thorong la pass\nFile:Thorong way.jpg | Back view from Thorong High Camp\nFile:View from High camp.jpg | View from High Camp\nFile:Tilicho-way.jpg | on the way to Tilicho Lake Khangsar\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Annapurna Circuit}}\n<!-- PLEASE DO ''not'' ADD BLOGS OR COMMERCIAL LINKS OR IT WILL BE ADDED TO WIKIPEDIA BLACKLIST-->\n* {{Wikivoyage-inline|Annapurna Circuit}}\n[https://www.mountmania.com/annapurna-circuit-trek/map Annapurna Circuit Trek Map]\n[https://www.mountainmarttreks.com/pagegallery/91abc-12days.png Annapurna Circuit Altitude Map]\n\n[[Category:Hiking trails in Nepal]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Nepal]]\n[[Category:Pokhara]]\n[[File:Terraced land & Begnas Lake view.jpg|thumb|Terraced land & Begnas Lake view]]\n", "text_old": "{{Undisclosed paid|date=February 2020}}\n[[File:Under stars and snows.jpg|350px|thumb|View of [[Machapuchare|Mt. Machapuchare]] from Annapurna Base Camp]]\nThe '''Annapurna Circuit''' is a [[trekking|trek]] within the mountain ranges of central [[Nepal]]. The total length of the route varies between 160\u2013230&nbsp;km (100-145&nbsp;mi), depending on where motor transportation is used and where the trek is ended. This trek crosses two different river valleys and encircles the [[Annapurna Massif]]. The path reaches its highest point at [[Thorung La]] pass (5416m/17769&nbsp;ft), touching the edge of the [[Tibetan plateau]]. Practically all trekkers hike the route anticlockwise, as this way the daily altitude gain is slower, and crossing the high Thorong La pass is easier and safer.\n\nIn addition to the Annapurna Circuit Trek, Annapurna Seven Passes Trek or Annapurna Seven Hills trek is also popular in the region. However, this is less traversed and is off the beaten path trek in the region.   \n\nThe mountain scenery, seen at close quarters includes the Annapurna Massif (Annapurna I-IV), [[Dhaulagiri]], [[Machhapuchhre]], [[Manaslu]], [[Gangapurna]], [[Tilicho Peak]], [[Pisang Peak]], and [[Paungda Danda]].  Numerous other peaks of 6000-8000m in elevation rise from the Annapurna range.\n\nThe trek begins at [[Besisahar]] or Bhulbhule in the [[Marshyangdi]] river valley and concludes in the [[Kali Gandaki Gorge]]. Besisahar can be reached after a seven-hour drive from [[Kathmandu]].  The trail passes along paddy fields and into subtropical forests, several waterfalls and gigantic cliffs, and various villages. \n\nAnnapurna Circuit has often been voted as the best long-distance trek in the world, as it combined, in its old full form, a wide variety of climate zones from tropics at 600 m asl to the arctic at 5416 m asl at the Thorong La pass and cultural variety from Hindu villages at the low foothills to the Tibetan culture of Manang Valley and lower Mustang. Continuing construction of a road has shortened the trail and changed the villages. The Beisahar-Manag road has been built which passes through the trekking trail most of the time.  With construction of the road, mountain biking is becoming popular, with Mustang in particular becoming one of the world's most popular mountain biking destinations.\n\n== Standard trek duration ==\n{{wide image|Annapurna Massif Panorama.jpg|990px|View of Annapurna massif near [[Manang]], [[Nepal]].}}\nThe [https://www.mantraadventure.com/trip/annapurna-circuit-trek/ Annapurna Base Circuit trek] usually takes about 15\u201320 days,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.alienadv.com/faq/10/Annapurna-Circuit-Trek/|title=Annapurna Circuit Trek|access-date=2016-08-23}}</ref> leaving from Kathmandu with a stopover in [[Pokhara]] before returning to the capital.<ref name=\":0\" /> The trail is moderate to fairly challenging and makes numerous river crossings over steel and wooden [[suspension bridge]]s. Tea houses and lodges along the circuit are available for meals and accommodations. Some groups may opt for tents but these are typically only for those destined for side trips away from lodges such as climbing a peak.<ref name=\":0\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wanderingsasquatch.com/how-to-hike-the-annapurna-circuit/|title=How to Hike the Annapurna Circuit|date=2013-06-13|language=en-US|access-date=2016-08-23}}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}}\n\n'''Outline Itinerary'''\n[[File:Marsyangdi river valley near Pisang.jpg|thumb|right|350px|[[Paungda Danda]] and Marsyangdi river valley near [[Pisang]]]]\nDay 01 - From Kathmandu, travel west to [[Besisahar]] [820m/2690&nbsp;ft] via private vehicle or public bus, taking six to seven hours.\n\nDay 02 - Trek to [[Khudi, Nepal|Khudi]] [790m/2592&nbsp;ft]\n\nDay 03 - Trek to [[Bahundanda]] [1310m/4298&nbsp;ft]\n\nDay 04 - Trek to [[Jagat, Nepal|Jagat]] [1290m/4232&nbsp;ft]\n\nDay 05 - Trek to [[Dharapani, Gandaki|Dharapani]] [1920m/6299&nbsp;ft]\n\nDay 06 - Trek to [[Chame, Nepal|Chame]] [2630m/8629&nbsp;ft]\n\nDay 07 - Trek to Upper/Lower [[Pisang]] [3190m/10466&nbsp;ft]\n\nDay 08 - Trek to [[Manang]] [3520m/11549&nbsp;ft]\n\nDay 09 - Rest day in Manang [3520m/11549&nbsp;ft]\n\nDay 10 - Trek to [[Letdar]] [4250m/13944&nbsp;ft]\n\nDay 11 - Trek to [[Thorung Phedi]] [4500m/14764&nbsp;ft]\n\nDay 12 - Trek to [[Muktinath]] [3800m/12467&nbsp;ft], crossing the [[Thorung La]] en route\n\nDay 13 - Trek to [[Marpha]] [2665m/8743&nbsp;ft]\n\nDay 14 - Trek to [[Lete, Nepal|Lete]] [2470m/8104&nbsp;ft] (now often with car or mountainbike)\n\nDay 15 - Trek to [[Tatopani, Myagdi|Tatopani]] [1160m/3806&nbsp;ft] (now often with car or mountainbike, day 14)\n\nDay 16 - Trek to [[Ghorepani]] [2775m/9104&nbsp;ft]\n\nDay 17 - Trek to [[Birethanti]] [1050m/3445&nbsp;ft] and travel to [[Pokhara]]\n\nDay 18 - Return to Kathmandu [1400m/4593&nbsp;ft]\n<ref>see more itinerary</ref>\nDepending on the speed of the trekkers, number and length of side trips and rest days taken, acclimatization, weather and where the trek is finished, hiking the Annapurna Circuit can take anything from 8 to 25 days. Many trekkers short on time choose to fly out from [[Jomsom Airport]], which shortens the trek by 6 days compared to the original AC.\n\nIt is also possible to continue from Ghorepani to Tadapani, [[Ghandruk]], Landruk and then to Phedi, which follows the old Annapurna Circuit from the time when the road was not yet extended to Beni. This more faithful variation takes three days instead of the shorter one-day exit from Ghorepani to Pokhara outlined above. A popular addition to the AC is a visit to Annapurna Base Camp, ABC (also called [[Annapurna Sanctuary]]). This trail turns to the north from Tadapani and rejoins the old AC at either Ghandruk or Landruk. A visit to the ABC adds about 5 days to the duration of the Annapurna Circuit, slightly less than the normal trek duration to ABC, as trekkers coming from the AC are already acclimatized and \"trail hardened\".\n\nIt is recommended that trekkers take the high trail from [[Pisang]] via [[Ghyaru]] and Ngawal to Manang, as the views are spectacular and the two villages along the route are some of the best preserved samples of Tibetan style villages still in their original state. Sleeping in either of these villages assists with acclimatization, as they are located already higher than Manang. Another side trip gaining popularity is the visit to [[Tilicho Lake|Tilicho Tal]], a lake. There are now lodges along the trail and near the lake at so-called Tilicho Base Camp, so tents are no longer required. If one wishes to cross to Jomsom via the Tilicho route, outdoor camping (and thus a tent) is required.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nepal-dia.de/int__England/EV_Annapurna/EB_Tilicho/eb_tilicho.html|title=Tilicho- Trekking in Nepal Annapurna|website=www.nepal-dia.de|access-date=2016-08-23}}</ref> At certain times of year, snow conditions can make the crossing dangerous or prevent it altogether.\n\nIn October 2014, Seth Wolpin achieved the fastest known time in 72 hours and 4 minutes. He started in Besisahar and finished in Naya Pull, following all New Annapurna Trekking Trails.<ref>http://sethwolpin.com/2014/10/the-annapurna-circuit-going-round-and.html/</ref><ref>http://trailrunningnepal.org/annapurna-circuit-trek-fastest-known-time-fkt/</ref>\n\nIt is reported<ref>http://trailrunningnepal.org/new-annapurna-circuit-fastest-known-time-fkt/</ref> that, the previous record of the Annapurna Circuit held by Seth Wolpin has been recently surpassed by the Greek athlete and philanthropist Lefteris Paraskevas, who, in May 2017 completed the classic route of the Circuit, from Besisahar to Nayapulin, in 68 hours and 22 minutes, achieving thus a new Fastest Known Time for the route.\n\n== Annapurna circuit weather ==\nWhile much of the Himalayas cannot be trekked in the wet season, much of the Annapurna circuit actually sits within a [[rain shadow]]. This means that it is possible to trek most parts of the circuit all year-round, including the monsoon period.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nTrekking in the wet season is often encouraged as hikers avoid the crowds that plague the summer months. However, the days are often damp and many of the views are obscured by cloud.\n\n=== October \u2013 November ===\nThis is the most popular hiking season in Nepal. Due to the recent monsoons, everything along the circuit is refreshed, clean and vibrant. Views are usually clear and the night sky is extremely visible. Though the weather is generally warm, nighttime temperatures drop below freezing. This is the busiest period on the circuit and tea houses book up very quickly.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Best time to trek the Annapurna Circuit - Kandoo Adventures|url = http://www.trekkinginnepal.org/annapurna-circuit-weather/|website = Kandoo Adventures|access-date = 2016-01-19|language = en-gb|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160126171358/http://www.trekkinginnepal.org/annapurna-circuit-weather/|archive-date = 2016-01-26|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\n=== December \u2013 March ===\nThis is the coldest period on the circuit. Depending on the altitude, day time temperatures will be cold and night time temperatures drop well below freezing. The trade off is that the trails are much less busy. Thorung La Pass, which stands at over 5,400 meters, is often blocked with snow and may be closed for days on end. Unless the snow blocks most trails, tea houses still remain open during this period. Clouds prevail more frequently, but clear days are still common. Towards March the rhododendrons start flowering, which brings hill sides alive with flaming colours. Unfortunately, this period is also when avalanches are most common. Completing the circuit might be possible during December but from January onward it becomes quite challenging and should be avoided unless advised by the locals.\n\n=== April \u2013 May ===\nBecause of the warming weather, April to May is the second most popular trekking season on the Annapurna Circuit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://trailblazer-guides.com/book/trekking-in-the-annapurna-region/when-to-go|title=Trailblazer Guide Books|website=trailblazer-guides.com|access-date=2016-08-23}}</ref> Most of the snow has dissipated, leaving crystal clear skies. There is often a strange haze that can be seen from the lower altitudes during May. However, this soon passes and cannot be seen from higher up the trail. As the monsoon period builds towards the end of May, the days become hotter and more humid which makes trekking at lower altitude quite uncomfortable.\n\n=== June \u2013 September ===\nThis is the monsoon period. Although there are stories of torrential downpours, mudslides and hordes of leeches, this is rarely the case on the Annapurna Circuit, particular the northern section. Whilst the south section of the Annapurna Circuit near Pokhara does get a lot of rain, the northern parts often receive less than 10% of the precipitation due to the location within a [[rain shadow]]. The upside of trekking in the monsoon period is that many of the flora species flower during this period, making the trek exceptionally beautiful. This is also the time when the Tilicho Lake side trek is relatively easier.\n\n== History ==\n\nThe Annapurna area was opened to foreign trekkers in 1977 after the disputes between CIA backed [[Kham]]pa guerrillas operating from the area into Tibet, and the local populace and Nepal army were settled. The original trek started from the market town of Dhumre situated at the Kathmandu - Pokhara highway and ended in Pokhara, and took about 23 days to complete. Road construction started in early 1980s both from Dhumre to the north and from Pokhara to the west and then up the Kali Gandaki valley. The road has now reached Chamje on the [[Marsyangdi]] river valley and Muktinath on the Kali Gandaki side. Of the trek's original 23 days, only 5 walking days of the trek are now without a motor road. In places new trails and routes have been marked so that the road can be partly avoided. The existence of the road has nevertheless changed the area, appearance, and atmosphere of the villages. The road facilitates transport, increasing the popularity of mountain biking in the area. Since 2011, companies in Muktinath and Jomsom rent out mountain bikes to tourists. As the road sees very little traffic, and one can ride downhill (dirt road and/or single track) from Muktinath to Tatopani and descend almost 3000 meters in 2\u20133 days.\n\nNew areas near Annapurna have been opened for trekkers in the past years, such as Upper Mustang, Naar-Pho Valley, Manaslu and Tsum Valley. Currently, trekking these areas is restricted and subject to extra permits, costs, and other limitations.\n\n==2014 blizzard==\n{{main article|2014 Nepal snowstorm disaster}}\nIn October 2014, a sudden [[blizzard]] killed over 43 people, half of whom were Nepalese.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/oct/16/nepal-blizzard-survivor-deaths-annapurna-refuge Annapurna blizzard]</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/21/world/asia/nepal-tragedy-reverberates-across-borders.html?hp&action=click&pgtype=Homepage&version=HpSumSmallMediaHigh&module=second-column-region&region=top-news&WT.nav=top-news&_r=0 Nepalese tragedy]</ref>  It was caused by the tail end of a dying cyclone which had ravaged the eastern coast of India; there were about 350 hikers caught in the blizzard.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/17/world/asia/hikers-blizzard-nepal.html?hp&action=click&pgtype=Homepage&version=HpSum&module=second-column-region&region=top-news&WT.nav=top-news Hikers caught in blizzard]</ref>\n\n== Communications ==\nMultiple locations of the trek circuit now have an Internet connection. This multi-district circuit's trekkers can use wireless internet across different districts like in Kaski, Myagdi, Lamjung and Mustang. Cellular 3G is also available at some locations.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Annapurna trekking circuit villages get Wi-Fi Internet \u2022 TechSansar.com|url = http://techsansar.com/tech-news/annapurna-trekking-circuit-wifi-internet/|website = |publisher = |accessdate = 2015-12-06|language = en-US}}</ref>{{coord|28.794671|N|83.937368|E|dim:80000_region:NP-GA_type:mountain_source:dewiki|display=title}}\n\n==Annapurna circuit trek gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Thorong-trail.jpg | On the way to thorong la pass\nFile:Thorong way.jpg | Back view from Thorong High Camp\nFile:View from High camp.jpg | View from High Camp\nFile:Tilicho-way.jpg | on the way to Tilicho Lake Khangsar\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Annapurna Circuit}}\n<!-- PLEASE DO ''not'' ADD BLOGS OR COMMERCIAL LINKS OR IT WILL BE ADDED TO WIKIPEDIA BLACKLIST-->\n* {{Wikivoyage-inline|Annapurna Circuit}}\n[https://www.mountmania.com/annapurna-circuit-trek/map Annapurna Circuit Trek Map]\n[https://www.mountainmarttreks.com/pagegallery/91abc-12days.png Annapurna Circuit Altitude Map]\n\n[[Category:Hiking trails in Nepal]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Nepal]]\n[[Category:Pokhara]]\n[[File:Terraced land & Begnas Lake view.jpg|thumb|Terraced land & Begnas Lake view]]\n", "name_user": "Cjrother", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStandard trek duration:reword", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Annapurna_Circuit"}
{"title_page": "Tom Kennedy (footballer)", "text_new": "{{short description|Footballer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=June 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name            = Tom Kennedy\n| image           = Tomkennedy3.jpg\n| fullname        = Thomas Gordon Kennedy\n| height          = \n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1985|6|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place     = [[Bury, Greater Manchester|Bury]], England\n| position        = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| years1 = 2002\u20132007  | clubs1 = [[Bury F.C.|Bury]]                                          | caps1  = 143 | goals1  = 5\n| years2 = 2007\u20132010  | clubs2 = [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]]                                | caps2  = 137 | goals2  = 9\n| years3 = 2010\u20132012  | clubs3 = [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]]                      | caps3  = 6   | goals3  = 0\n| years4 = 2010\u20132011  | clubs4 = \u2192 [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]] (loan)                       | caps4  = 6   | goals4  = 0\n| years5 = 2011       | clubs5 = \u2192 [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]] (loan)   | caps5  = 14  | goals5  = 0\n| years6 = 2011       | clubs6 = \u2192 [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]] (loan)   | caps6  = 10  | goals6  = 0\n| years7 = 2012\u20132014  | clubs7 = [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]]                                  | caps7  = 68  | goals7  = 1\n| years8 = 2014\u20132016  | clubs8 = [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]]                                | caps8  = 41  | goals8  = 0\n| years9 = 2014       | clubs9 = \u2192 [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] (loan)                                 | caps9  = 2   | goals9  = 0\n| years10 = 2014\u20132015 | clubs10 = \u2192 [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] (loan)                      | caps10 = 5   | goals10 = 0\n| years11 = 2016\u20132017 | clubs11 = [[A.F.C. Fylde|AFC Fylde]]                                 | caps11 = 38  | goals11 = 0\n| years12 = 2017\u20132018 | clubs12 = [[Bangor City F.C.|Bangor City]]                           | caps12 = 27  | goals12 = 0\n| totalcaps = 497\n| totalgoals = 15\n| club-update =\n}}\n'''Thomas Gordon Kennedy''' (born 24 June 1985) is an English former professional [[Association football|footballer]]. Kennedy has had spells at [[Bury F.C.|Bury]], [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]], [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] and (on loan) [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]]. He mostly plays at [[Defender (association football)|left-back]]. In May 2018, he announced he was retiring from professional football after a spell at [[Bangor City F.C.|Bangor City]] in order to concentrate on his post-football career.\n\n==Club career==\nKennedy was born in Bury, England and grew up supporting his local team [[Bury F.C.|Bury]]. His father, Keith Kennedy, played for [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] while his uncle, [[Alan Kennedy]] was a [[Defender (football)|defender]] for [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] and [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Maden's double sends kids through|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5940837.Maden_s_double_sends_kids_through/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=29 October 2002|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Liverpool legend Alan Kennedy backs nephew Tom to be big hit at Leicester City|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/liverpool-legend-alan-kennedy-backs-nephew-tom-big-hit-leicester-city/story-12063994-detail/story.html|publisher=Leicester Mercury|date=15 June 2010|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs he started playing football, Kennedy revealed he started out playing in the central midfielder but as the years go by, he was pushed to playing out in different positions, leading him to play as a left-back, where he played today.<ref>{{cite news|title=Class is in the blood for Fylde's Tom Kennedy|url=http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/sport/football/afc-fylde/class-is-in-the-blood-for-fylde-s-kennedy-1-8060247|publisher=Blackpool Gazette|date=10 August 2016|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Bury===\nKennedy began his career at Bury and after progressing the ranks of Bury youth team,<ref>{{cite news|title=Nugent set for big time|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5926445.Nugent_set_for_big_time/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=31 December 2002|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Armstrong's debt to Bury youth policy|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5971305.Armstrong_s_debt_to_Bury_youth_policy/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=1 May 2002|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Kennedy signed a contract with the club in February 2003, keeping him until August 2004.<ref>{{cite news|title=Young guns ready to shoot to the top|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5914275.Young_guns_ready_to_shoot_to_the_top/|publisher=Bury Times|date=5 March 2003|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nHis impressive performance in the reserve earned him a first team in the 2003\u201304 season after being called\u2013up to the pre\u2013season tour with Bury.<ref>{{cite news|title=Stuart leaves Gigg to join Southend United|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5900058.Stuart_leaves_Gigg_to_join_Southend/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=5 June 2003|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Following this, Kennedy then made his debut as a 54th-minute substitute in Bury's 5\u20133 defeat away at [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]] on 16 September 2003.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bury FC: Shakers put through the Mill|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5881635.Bury_FC__Shakers_put_through_the_Mill/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=19 September 2003|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> His first start for Bury came in their 2\u20131 win over [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]] in the [[Football League Trophy]] on 3 November 2003.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thompson stakes his claim|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5873906.Thompson_stakes_his_claim/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=4 November 2003|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> His performance in the first team earned him Bury FC player-of-the-month for December.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bury FC: Tom's a chip off the old block|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5863244.Bury_FC__Tom_s_a_chip_off_the_old_block/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=9 January 2004|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> With 21 appearance in the first team, Kennedy signed a two-year contract with Bury.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kennedy signs new Bury deal|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bury/3579065.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=29 March 2004|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref> Kennedy then became Bury's first choice left back, starting all but one of Bury's remanding fixtures in the 2003\u201304 season, finish the season with 27 league appearances in his first full season at the club. At the end of the 2003\u201304 season, Kennedy was awarded the Young Player of the Year award.<ref>{{cite news|title=Glyn's glittering haul|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5839267.Glyn_s_glittering_haul/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=25 May 2004|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nDespite being linked a move away from Bury during and after the 2003\u201304 season,<ref>{{cite news|title=Barrow calls for Shakers focus by Phil Thorp|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5865508.Barrow_calls_for_Shakers_focus_by_Phil_Thorp/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=24 December 2003|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Kennedy boost for Shakers|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5850317.Kennedy_boost_for_Shakers/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=30 March 2004|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Kennedy stayed at the club for the 2004\u201305 season and was given a number three shirt.<ref>{{cite news|title=Newby gets his number|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5830082.Newby_gets_his_number/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=13 July 2004|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> After being told by the club's management that he would fight for the first team place, Kennedy managed to regained his first team place in the 2004\u201305 season and though he played in the left\u2013back position, he once played in the defensive midfield position.<ref>{{cite news|title=Shakers tough it out|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5830586.Shakers_tough_it_out/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=9 July 2004|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Shakers boss so excited about new venture|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5825439.Shakers_boss_so_excited_about_new_venture/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=9 August 2004|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=21 years, now Shakers dream of ending derby bogey|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5788664.21_years__now_Shakers_dream_of_ending_derby_bogey/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=1 April 2005|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Kennedy then scored his first goal, in a 2\u20132 draw away at [[Boston United F.C.|Boston United]] on 12 February 2005.<ref>{{cite news|title=Battling Shakers make their point|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5795105.Battling_Shakers_make_their_point/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=14 February 2005|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Despite the club's financial situation,<ref>{{cite news|title=Kennedy's pledge for the future|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5799966.Kennedy_s_pledge_for_the_future/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=18 January 2005|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Kennedy stayed and started all Bury's 46 games of the 2004\u201305 season scoring once, He made a total of 50 appearances, including making 46 league appearance, for Bury in all competitions throughout the season.\n\nIn the 2005\u201306 season, Kennedy continued to remain in the first team place and then scored his first goal of the season on 24 September 2005 in a 2\u20131 away defeat at [[Oxford United F.C.|Oxford United]] after coming on as a 59th-minute substitute.<ref>{{cite news|title=Casper optimistic despite defeat|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/6223680.Casper_optimistic_despite_defeat/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=24 September 2005|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Kennedy then scored in a 3\u20132 loss at home to [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] on 29 October 2005,<ref>{{cite news|title=Bury blunders prove so costly|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/6227085.Bury_blunders_prove_so_costly/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=29 October 2005|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> followed up by scoring a week later on 5 November 2005, in a 2\u20132 home draw with [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]] in the first round of the [[FA Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Cup stalemate as Bury play on Iron's failings: BURY 2, SCUNTHORPE UNITED 2|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/6228448.Cup_stalemate_as_Bury_play_on_Iron_s_failings__BURY_2__SCUNTHORPE_UNITED_2/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=10 November 2005|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> However, between December 2005 and March 2006, Kennedy spent the months sidelined when he suffered hamstring injuries on three occasions.<ref>{{cite news|title=Shakers aim to madden hatters!|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/6233509.Shakers_aim_to_madden_hatters_/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=29 December 2005|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bury bounce back thanks to Speight double|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/6235301.Bury_bounce_back_thanks_to_Speight_double/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=16 January 2006|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Boss sharpens up the Shakers|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/6235840.Boss_sharpens_up_the_Shakers/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=20 January 2006|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> After returning to the first team from injury against [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]] on 18 March 2006, coming on as a second-half substitute,<ref>{{cite news|title=Shot Shy Bury Pay The Price|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/710202.Shot_shy_Bury_pay_the_price/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=18 March 2006|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Kennedy scored his first goals in four months, in Bury's 1\u20131 draw at home with [[Oxford United F.C.|Oxford United]] on 21 March 2006.<ref>{{cite news|title=Shakers waste penalty gift|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/712618.Shakers_waste_penalty_gift/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=22 March 2006|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> On 8 April 2006, Kennedy later scored his fourth goal of the season, in a 3\u20131 loss at home to [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Casper Unhappy as Shakers Let It Slip|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/728136.Casper_unhappy_as_Shakers_let_it_slip/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=10 April 2006|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> In the 2005\u201306 season, Kennedy finished the season, making 35 appearances and scoring five times in all competitions. At the end of the 2005\u201306 season, Kennedy signed a one-year contract extension, keeping him until 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tom Kennedy signs on with the Shakers|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11774/2377817|publisher=Sky Sports|date=2 February 2007|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2006\u201307 season, Kennedy continued to be in the first team regular at Bury and then set up two goals, in a 2\u20132 draw against [[Accrington Stanley F.C.|Accrington Stanley]] on 26 September 2006.<ref>{{cite news|title=Match Report: Bury 2 \u2013 2 Accrington Stanley|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/942062.Bury_2_Accrington_Stanley_2/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=26 September 2006|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=You'll be the best \u2013 Casper|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/sport/978471.You_ll_be_the_best___Casper/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=19 October 2006|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Kennedy made his last appearances for The Shakers in their 1\u20130 home loss to [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] on 24 March 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=Another Defeat For Embattled Shakers|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/1286000.Another_defeat_for_embattled_Shaker/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=26 March 2007|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> However, as the 2006\u201307 season progressed, Kennedy went on to make thirty\u2013nine appearances and was released by the club at the end of the 2006\u201307 season, which he seek new challenges.<ref>{{cite news|title=Six go as Shakers announce clear-out|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/sport/1386837.Six_go_as_Shakers_announce_clear_out/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=9 May 2007|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Fresh start needed for Kennedy|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/sport/1387902.Fresh_start_needed_for_Kennedy/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=10 May 2007|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nKennedy left Bury in 2007 to join local rivals [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]] after making 158 appearances for his home town club scoring six times between 2003 when he made his debut for the club until 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rochdale sign Muirhead & Kennedy|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rochdale/6718723.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=4 June 2007|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref> Additionally, Kennedy was able to surpass his father's goal tally while playing for Bury, a prediction he made two years ago.<ref>{{cite news|title=Teenage Shaker has his dad's tally in sight|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5795010.Teenage_Shaker_has_his_dad_s_tally_in_sight/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=18 February 2005|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Rochdale===\n[[File:tomkennedy.jpg|thumb|150px|Kennedy playing for Rochdale in March 2015.]]\n\nKennedy signed for Rochdale on 4 June 2007 after four seasons at Bury.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rochdale sign Muirhead & Kennedy|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rochdale/6718723.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=4 June 2007|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nKennedy made his debut, in the opening game of the season on 11 August 2007, in a 3\u20130 loss against [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Reality check for Dale in season opener|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/2341/reality-check-for-dale-in-season-opener|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=11 August 2007|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Since making his Rochdale debut, Kennedy quickly became a first team regular, playing in the left\u2013back position.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hill warns players to expect a tough match against Wrexham|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/933/hill-warns-players-to-expect-a-tough-match-against-wrexham|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=30 November 2007|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> After suffering an illness that saw him missed one match in late\u2013December,<ref>{{cite news|title=Dale manager Hill confident of extending six match unbeaten run|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/887/dale-manager-hill-confident-of-extending-six-match-unbeaten-run|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=31 December 2007|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Kennedy returned from injury and set up one of the goals, in a 3\u20131 win over [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]] on 1 January 2008,<ref>{{cite news|title=First half strikes sink Darlington|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/22/first-half-strikes-sink-darlington|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=1 January 2008|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> followed up by scoring his first goal for the club, in a 1\u20130 win over [[Wycombe Wanderers F.C.|Wycombe Wanderers]] on 11 January 2008.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wycombe Wanderers 0\u20131 Rochdale|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/7172946.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=11 January 2008|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref> He scored his second goal of the season on 29 January 2008, in a 4\u20130 win over [[Chester F.C.|Chester]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Ellison sees red to make it all too easy for Dale|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/583/ellison-sees-red-to-make-it-all-too-easy-for-dale|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=29 January 2008|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> In the [[2008 Football League play-offs|play-offs]] against [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Kennedy looking forward to derby|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/8451/kennedy-looking-forward-to-derby|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=23 April 2008|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Kennedy scored the second penalty in a penalty shoot-out and Rochdale would win the game to go to the [[2008 Football League Two play-off Final|final]] to face [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]], after [[Jason Kennedy (footballer)|Jason Kennedy]] miss the final spot kick. After the match, Kennedy reflected the 2007\u201308 season, stating that the club have had an 'amazing' season and described this an unbelievable feeling.<ref>{{cite news|title=Amazing season for Dale \u2013 Kennedy|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rochdale/7408572.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=19 May 2008|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref> However, Rochdale would succumb 3\u20132 to Stockport County, remaining in League Two for the following season. Despite this, he went on to finish his first season, making 46 appearances (43 in the league) and scoring two times in all competitions.\n\nIn the 2008\u201309 season, Kennedy started the season well when he helped the side go to their winning ways following the play\u2013offs defeat to Stockport County<ref>{{cite news|title=Dale ready for season opener|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/12632/dale-ready-for-season-opener|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=7 August 2008|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> and scored a winning goal from a free kick in stoppage time, in a 2\u20131 win over [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]] on 20 September 2008.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rochdale 2 \u2013 1 Chesterfield|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_div_3/7614072.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=20 September 2008|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> It wasn't until on 23 January 2009 when he scored his second goal of the season, in a 3\u20132 loss against [[Dagenham & Redbridge F.C.|Dagenham & Redbridge]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Dagenham & Redbridge 3 \u2013 2 Rochdale|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/7844330.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=23 January 2009|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> A week later, Kennedy signed a contract extension, keeping him until the end of the 2009\u201310 season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dale duo extend deals|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11750/4888749|publisher=Sky Sports|date=2 February 2009|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref> Following this, he scored two more goals later in the season against [[Macclesfield Town F.C.|Macclesfield Town]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Macclesfield Town 0 \u2013 1 Rochdale|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/7876781.st|publisher=BBC Sport|date=14 February 2009|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> and [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Rochdale 1 (Kennedy 37 pen) Brentford 2 (Rhodes 9, MacDonald 15) \u2013 Full Time Report|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/viewer?NewsID=20464|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=24 February 2009|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Since the start of the season, Kennedy featured in every league game until he missed out on the last game of the season, due to resting ahead of the play\u2013offs.<ref>{{cite news|title=Can Dale end 35 year wait?|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/23739/can-dale-end-35-year-wait|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=7 May 2009|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> However, once again, Rochdale lost 2\u20131 on aggregate to [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Gillingham 2 (Jackson 13, 58 pen) Rochdale 1 (Dagnall 36) - Full Time Report|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/23808/gillingham-2-jackson-13-58-pen-rochdale-1-dagnall-36-full-time-report|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=10 May 2009|accessdate=17 May 2017}}</ref> Despite this, Kennedy was voted into the PFA League Two Team of The Year, voted for by his fellow professionals in League Two, for the 2008\u201309 season at the PFA awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10441~1645190,00.html|title=Hilly in Praise of TK|publisher=Rochdale AFC official website|date=1 May 2009|accessdate=1 May 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090502233424/http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10441~1645190,00.html|archivedate=2 May 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> He was also voted Defender of the Year for the 2008\u201309 season following Rochdale's unsuccessful promotion push.<ref>{{cite news|title=Supporters Trust donates \u00a31330 for pre-season tour|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/24206/supporters-trust-donates-\u00a31330-for-preseason-tour|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=18 May 2009|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2009\u201310 season, Kennedy started the season well when he scored the only goal in the game from a penalty, in a 1\u20130 win over [[Aldershot Town F.C.|Aldershot Town]] on 15 August 2009.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rochdale 1 (T. Kennedy 90 pen) Aldershot 0 \u2013 Full Time Report|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/28421/rochdale-1-t-kennedy-90-pen-aldershot-0-%E2%80%93-full-time-report|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=15 August 2009|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> He later scored two more goals by the end of the 2009 against Bury<ref>{{cite news|title=16 years of derby day hurt end in fine style|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/29019/16-years-of-derby-day-hurt-end-in-fine-style|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=30 August 2009|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> and [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Rochdale 2 \u2013 1 Barnet|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/8293297.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=10 October 2009|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> His performance throughout the 2009\u201310 season led Manager [[Keith Hill (footballer)|Keith Hill]] commented in March 2010 that Kennedy is considered as the best left-back in League Two.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rochdale boss Keith Hill praises Tom Kennedy|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rochdale/8570326.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=16 March 2010|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref> After helping the club finished third place that saw them promoted to League One, Kennedy finished the 2009\u201310 season, making 47 (44 in the league) appearances and scoring three times in all competitions. Once again, Kennedy was voted into the PFA League Two Team of The Year for the 2009\u201310 season at the PFA awards.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rooney is PFA player of the year|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/8643305.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=25 April 2010|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the season, Kennedy was offered a new contract by the club, as his contract set to expires in July.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dales Release Players|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/41053/dale-release-players|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=13 May 2010|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> However, he announced his intention to leave Rochdale,<ref>{{cite news|title=Kennedy set for Dale exit|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11715/6176739|publisher=Sky Sports|date=28 May 2010|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref> with clubs in Championship like [[Doncaster Rovers F.C.|Doncaster Rovers]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Rovers eye Rochdale raid|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/6136315|publisher=Sky Sports|date=13 May 2010|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref> [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]], [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]] all tracking to sign Kennedy.\n\n===Leicester City===\nOn 10 June 2010, the [[Football League Championship|Championship]] side [[Leicester City FC|Leicester City]] agreed a pre-contract with Kennedy and the left back officially joined Leicester on 1 July,<ref name=\"Foxes grab Kennedy\">{{Cite web| title=Foxes Grab Kennedy| url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11688_6199418,00.html| publisher=British Sky Broadcasting| work=www.skysports.com| date=10 June 2010| accessdate=10 June 2010}}</ref> having rejected a chance to move Doncaster Rovers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kennedy set for Rovers|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/6190633|publisher=Sky Sports|date=4 June 2010|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref> After moving, Kennedy say he made an easy decision to join Leicester City.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tom Kennedy says Leicester City switch was easy|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/leicester_city/8734631.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=11 June 2010|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nKennedy made his Leicester City debut in the first round of the League Cup, starting the whole game, in a 4\u20133 win over [[Macclesfield Town F.C.|Macclesfield Town]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Leicester City edge out Macclesfield Town in Carling Cup clash|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/leicester-city-edge-macclesfield-carling-cup-clash/story-12027572-detail/story.html|publisher=Leicester Mercury|date=11 August 2010|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> It wasn't until on 28 September 2010 when he made his league debut for the club away, in a 4\u20133 loss against [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]], playing the whole game.<ref>{{cite news|title=Norwich City 4 \u2013 3 Leicester City|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/9031746.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=28 September 2010|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> During the match, he was conceded a penalty when he was penalised for handball.<ref>{{cite news|title=Match verdict: Battling Leicester City rue defensive errors against Norwich City|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/match-verdict-battling-leicester-city-rue-defensive-errors-norwich/story-12081213-detail/story.html|publisher=Leicester Mercy|date=29 September 2010|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> After the match, Kennedy acknowledged the fault of giving away the penalty, but hopes for first team football in the near future.<ref>{{cite news|title=Defender Tom Kennedy says it's down to Leicester City players to stop the rot|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/s-stop-rot/story-12080758-detail/story.html|publisher=Leicester Mercury|date=30 September 2010|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Despite stating that he adapted to the team,<ref>{{cite news|title=Defender Tom Kennedy has vowed that Leicester City fans are in for a treat|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/tom-kennedy-says-leicester-city-fans-treat/story-12038366-detail/story.html|publisher=Leicester Mercury|date=19 July 2010|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> his time at Leicester City was unhappy over lack of first team opportunities at Leicester City as he spent time on the bench more often, as well as, becoming the third choice player in the left\u2013back position behind [[Bruno Berner]] and [[Greg Cunningham]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Frustrated Tom Kennedy is glad to be on the move from Leicester City|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/frustrated-tom-kennedy-glad-leicester-city/story-12055761-detail/story.html|publisher=Leicester Mercury|date=3 November 2010|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> In his first season at Leicester City, Kennedy went on to make four appearances in all competitions.\n\nAhead of the 2011\u201312 season, Kennedy stated that he has no future at Leicester City.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tom Kennedy looks at life away from Leicester City|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/tom-kennedy-looks-life-away-leicester-city/story-12082573-detail/story.html|publisher=Leicester Mercury|date=1 April 2011|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> After returning from a loan spell at Peterborough United, Kennedy returned to Leicester City<ref name=\"Kennedy Peterborough Telegraph\"/> and was put straight into the starting line-up against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] to finally make his senior debut for the club under [[Nigel Pearson]], 19 months after signing him.<ref>{{cite news|title=Leicester City back to winning ways|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/leicester-city-winning-ways/story-14303368-detail/story.html|publisher=Leicester Mercury|date=2 January 2012|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Though he made seven more appearances in all competitions later in the season, his first team opportunities continued to be limited, as he spent the rest of the season on the substitute bench.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kennedy presses his claim to start|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/kennedy-presses-claim-start/story-15384773-detail/story.html|publisher=Leicester Mercury|date=3 March 2012|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> As a result, it was announced that Kennedy and the club came to a mutual agreement to terminate his contract on 29 August 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tom Kennedy set to move on from Leicester City|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/8029924|publisher=Sky Sports|date=29 August 2012|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Loan moves====\nOn 1 November 2010, Kennedy rejoined his old club Rochdale on loan until January due to lack of first team opportunities at Leicester City.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kennedy makes Rochdale return|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11719/6481525|publisher=Sky Sports|date=1 November 2010|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref> Kennedy's first match since leaving the club in the summer came on 13 November 2010, starting the whole, in a 2\u20130 loss against [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Match Report: Sheffield Wednesday 2 \u2013 0 Rochdale|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/49283/sheffield-wednesday-2-0-rochdale|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=13 November 2010|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> In the next game against [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] on 20 November 2010, Kennedy set up one of the goals, in a 3\u20133 draw.<ref>{{cite news|title=Match Report: Rochdale 3 \u2013 3 Swindon Town|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/49551/rochdale-3-3-swindon-town|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=20 November 2010|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> After making six appearance at Rochdale, Kennedy loan spell at Rochdale had ended in January 2011.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kennedy returns from loan spell|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11765/6651094|publisher=Sky Sports|date=11 January 2011|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 January 2011, Kennedy joined [[Football League One|League One]] club [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]] on loan until the end of the season, which could be made permanent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lcfc.com/page/LatestNews/0,,10274~2271424,00.html|title=Kennedy joins Peterborough United on Loan|publisher=LCFC.com|date=20 January 2011|accessdate=20 January 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110121162847/http://www.lcfc.com/page/LatestNews/0,,10274~2271424,00.html|archivedate=21 January 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The next day, on 21 January 2011, Kennedy made his debut, playing 90 minutes, in a 4\u20130 win over [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Posh 4, Hartlepool 0 \u2013 Happy return for Darren Ferguson|url=http://www.peterboroughtoday.co.uk/sport/football/posh/posh-4-hartlepool-0-happy-return-for-ferguson-1-2335660|publisher=Peterborough Today|date=21 January 2011|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Kennedy have since established himself in the starting eleven, playing in the left back position in defence. Having made 14 starts since joining the club, Kennedy said he expressed desire to stay at Peterborough United permanent at the end of the season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kennedy keen on Posh stay|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11712/6843100|publisher=Sky Sports|date=30 March 2011|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref> But, nothing came for it as in April, Kennedy suffered a knee ligament damage during a 2\u20130 win over [[Dagenham & Redbridge F.C.|Dagenham & Redbridge]], resulted his last appearance for Peterborough and would return to Leicester City for treatment.<ref>{{cite news|title=Peterborough United hit by Tom Kennedy knee injury|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/13039528|publisher=BBC Sport|date=11 April 2011|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref> At the end of the season with Peterborough promoted to the Championship, director of football [[Barry Fry]] expressed desire to sign Kennedy but feared his injury prevent his move back to the club<ref>{{cite news|title=Posh keen on duo's return|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11688/6963655|publisher=Sky Sports|date=2 June 2011|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 September 2011, Kennedy re-joined Peterborough for a second loan spell on a 3-month loan from Leicester.<ref>{{cite news|title=Leicester City's Tom Kennedy returns to Peterborough United|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/15126916|publisher=BBC Sport|date=30 September 2011|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref> However, Kennedy's first month at re\u2013joining the club suffered a setback, as he became a second choice left\u2013back player behind [[Craig Alcock]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Posh preview: Bristol City will be a team of wounded animal|url=http://www.peterboroughtoday.co.uk/sport/football/posh/posh-preview-bristol-city-will-be-a-team-of-wounded-animals-1-3151728|publisher=Peterborough Today|date=14 October 2011|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=POSH HOPING TO KEEP RYAN|url=http://www.peterboroughtoday.co.uk/sport/football/posh/posh-hoping-to-keep-ryan-1-3196677|publisher=Peterborough Today|date=29 October 2011|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> It wasn't until on 30 October 2011 when Kennedy made his second debut for the club, playing the whole game, in a 3\u20132 loss against [[Watford F.C.|Watford]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Watford 3 Posh 2: It's captain non-sensible!|url=http://www.peterboroughtoday.co.uk/sport/football/posh/watford-3-posh-2-it-s-captain-non-sensible-1-3200180|publisher=Peterborough Today|date=30 October 2011|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> After making ten appearance for the side in his second loan spell, Kennedy's second loan at Peterborough ended in January 2012.<ref name=\"Kennedy Peterborough Telegraph\">{{cite news|title=POSH MAKING FERGIE PROUD|url=http://www.peterboroughtoday.co.uk/sport/football/peterborough-united/posh-making-fergie-proud-1-3380400|publisher=Peterborough Today|date=2 January 2012|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Barnsley===\nAfter leaving Leicester City, Kennedy agreed non-contract terms with [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] until January 2013 on 21 September 2012 after a period training with the [[South Yorkshire]] club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-league.co.uk/championship/news/20120921/kennedy-completes-tykes-switch_2293322_2925868|title=Kennedy completes Tykes switch|publisher=The Football League|date=21 September 2012|accessdate=16 January 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715002149/http://www.football-league.co.uk/championship/news/20120921/kennedy-completes-tykes-switch_2293322_2925868|archivedate=15 July 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nKennedy made his debut on 22 September in a 5\u20130 win against [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19615055 \"Birmingham 0\u20135 Barnsley\"] BBC Sport. 22 September 2012. Retrieved 29 September 2012.</ref> However Kennedy initially struggled for first team opportunities, making just a handful of first team appearances; but since early January became a first team regular for the rest of the season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Barnsley: Tom Kennedy is ready to get ugly|url=http://www.thestar.co.uk/sport/football/sheffield-united/barnsley-tom-is-ready-to-get-ugly-1-5416774|publisher=The Star|date=16 February 2013|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> As a result, Kennedy signed a six-month contract as his non-contract agreement was about to expire.<ref>{{cite news|title=Barnsley: Defender gets six months Reds' deal|url=http://www.thestar.co.uk/sport/football/barnsley/barnsley-defender-gets-six-months-reds-deal-1-5321234|publisher=The Star|date=17 January 2013|accessdate=17 January 2013}}</ref> In a 6\u20130 loss against [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] on 13 April 2013, he received a straight red card when he \"brought down [[Ricardo Fuller]]\" and was the second Barnsley to be sent\u2013off in the game, as well as [[Stephen Dawson]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Football League Championship: Charlton Athletic hammer Barnsley 6 \u2013 0 at Oakwell|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/barnsley-vs-charlton/262180|publisher=Sky Sports|date=13 April 2013|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> He served a one\u2013match suspension<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barnsleyfc.co.uk/news/article/flitcroft-on-forest-clash-18042013-779968.aspx|title=Flitcroft on Nottingham Forest Clash|publisher=Barnsley F.C.|date=18 April 2013|accessdate=16 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170515201604/http://www.barnsleyfc.co.uk/news/article/flitcroft-on-forest-clash-18042013-779968.aspx|archivedate=15 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and returned to the first team, where he played three remaining matches later in the season, including the last game of the season, playing the whole game, in a 2\u20132 draw against [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]], a draw that saw Barnsley secure Championship status for another season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barnsleyfc.co.uk/news/article/the-reds-are-staying-up-807660.aspx|title=The Reds Are Staying Up!|publisher=Barnsley F.C.|date=4 May 2013|accessdate=16 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170515201511/http://www.barnsleyfc.co.uk/news/article/the-reds-are-staying-up-807660.aspx|archivedate=15 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> At the end of the 2012\u201313 season, Kennedy went on to make 24 appearances in all competitions and for his performance, Kennedy signed a two-year extension in the summer of 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=Barnsley: Tom Kennedy signs a new two-year deal at Oakwell|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22690879|publisher=BBC Sport|date=28 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2013\u201314 season, Kennedy switched number shirt from 33 to 4 this season<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barnsleyfc.co.uk/news/article/squad-numbers-28062013-885508.aspx|title=Squad Numbers|publisher=Barnsley F.C.|date=28 June 2013|accessdate=16 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170515202516/http://www.barnsleyfc.co.uk/news/article/squad-numbers-28062013-885508.aspx|archivedate=15 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and continued to be a first team regular for the side since the start of the season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Barnsley: Reds starlet backed to fulfil potential|url=http://www.thestar.co.uk/sport/football/barnsley-fc/barnsley-reds-starlet-backed-to-fulfil-potential-1-6016456|publisher=The Star|date=6 September 2013|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> In a 2\u20131 win over Huddersfield Town on 31 August 2013, he set up a goal for [[Marcus Pedersen]] to score the second goal for Barnsley in the game.<ref>{{cite news|title=Barnsley 2 \u2013 1 Huddersfield Town|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23822875|publisher=BBC Sport|date=31 August 2013|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Kennedy also assisted six more times later in the 2013\u201314 season, including assisting a winning goal, in a 1\u20130 win over [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] on 8 March 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=Barnsley 1 \u2013 0 Nottingham Forest|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/26395407|publisher=BBC Sport|date=8 March 2014|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Kennedy then scored his first goal for the club on 15 April 2014, scoring a winning goal, in a 2\u20131 against Charlton Athletic.<ref>{{cite news|title=Charlton Athletic 1 \u2013 2 Barnsley|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25817450|publisher=BBC Sport|date=15 April 2014|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> However, the club was eventually relegated to League One next season after losing 3\u20131 to [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] on 26 April 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=Middlesbrough 3 \u2013 1 Barnsley|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/27084041|publisher=BBC Sport|date=26 April 2014|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Despite missing out two times, due to being on the substitute bench unused, Kennedy finished his second season at Barnsley, making forty\u2013seven appearances and scoring once in all competitions.\n\nHowever, ahead of the 2014\u201315 season, Kennedy terminated his contract at Barnsley on 31 July 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barnsleyfc.co.uk/news/article/tom-kennedy-leaves-oakwell-30072014-1793231.aspx|title=Tom Kennedy Leaves Oakwell|publisher=Barnsley F.C.|date=31 July 2014|accessdate=16 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170515203819/http://www.barnsleyfc.co.uk/news/article/tom-kennedy-leaves-oakwell-30072014-1793231.aspx|archivedate=15 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> It came after when Kennedy, along with [[Martin Cranie]], did not travel to Italy with the squad for the club's pre-season training trip to Italy.<ref>{{cite news|title=Barnsley: Steele and O'Grady add to exodus|url=http://www.thestar.co.uk/sport/football/barnsley-fc/barnsley-steele-and-o-grady-add-to-exodus-1-6738529|publisher=The Star|date=18 July 2014|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Rochdale Return===\nOn 14 August 2014, Kennedy resigned for [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]] on a short-term deal until January 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tom Kennedy Returns To Rochdale|url=http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/news/article/tk-signs-1828999.aspx|publisher=Rochdale A.F.C.|accessdate=14 August 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516184745/http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/news/article/tk-signs-1828999.aspx|archivedate=16 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and reuniting with former manager Keith Hill.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/news/article/hill-tkdawson-1831034.aspx|title=Hill: Dawson & Kennedy|publisher=Rochdale A.F.C.|date=15 August 2014|accessdate=16 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516185000/http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/news/article/hill-tkdawson-1831034.aspx|archivedate=16 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nTwo days after signing for the club, Kennedy's second debut for the club came against Chesterfield, playing the whole game, in a 2\u20131 loss.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chesterfield 2 \u2013 1 Rochdale|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/28716649|publisher=BBC Sport|date=16 August 2014|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Although becoming a first team regular throughout August, Kennedy lost his first team place in the left\u2013back positions and was limited to six appearances by the time he went out on loan throughout January.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tom Kennedy out on loan to Bury|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/92106/tom-kennedy-out-on-loan-to-bury|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=24 October 2014|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> After returning to his parent club from loan spells, he signed a contract extension with the club, keeping him until the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/news/article/tom-kennedy-signs-contract-2273837.aspx|title=Tom Kennedy Signs Contract|publisher=Rochdale A.F.C.|date=16 February 2015|accessdate=16 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516191440/http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/news/article/tom-kennedy-signs-contract-2273837.aspx|archivedate=16 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> It wasn't until on 21 February 2015 when he returned to the first team for the first time since October, playing the whole game, in a 1\u20130 win over Chesterfield.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rochdale 1 \u2013 0 Chesterfield|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/94358/rochdale-1-0-chesterfield|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=21 February 2015|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Since then, Kennedy regained his first team place as a left\u2013back throughout the 2014\u201315 season, making twenty\u2013four appearances in all competitions and it was announced on 29 June 2015 that Kennedy signed a new two-year deal.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tom Kennedy Signs New Contract|url=http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/news/article/tom-kennedy-signs-new-contract-2510937.aspx?|publisher=Rochdale A.F.C.|accessdate=29 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516192704/http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/news/article/tom-kennedy-signs-new-contract-2510937.aspx|archivedate=16 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn his second season at Rochdale, Kennedy continued to regain his first team place at the start of the 2015\u201316 season, but soon around October, he was demoted to the substitute for the most of the season, due to competitions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/news/article/injury-update-ashley-eastham-2903420.aspx|title=Injury Update: Ashley Eastham|publisher=Rochdale A.F.C.|date=15 January 2016|accessdate=16 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516193645/http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/news/article/injury-update-ashley-eastham-2903420.aspx|archivedate=16 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> After returning to the first team in January, Kennedy made his 200th appearance in his Rochdale career on 30 January 2016, in a 2\u20131 win over [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/news/article/appearance-milestones-for-tom-kennedy-olly-lancashire-2932659.aspx|title=Appearance Milestones For Tom Kennedy & Olly Lancashire|publisher=Rochdale A.F.C.|date=1 February 2016|accessdate=16 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516193656/http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/news/article/appearance-milestones-for-tom-kennedy-olly-lancashire-2932659.aspx|archivedate=16 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> However, Kennedy, once again, lost his first team place at Rochdale and didn't play again for the rest of the 2015\u201316 season. Despite this, he went on to make twenty\u2013one appearances in all competitions.\n\nOn 26 May 2016, Kennedy left Rochdale by mutual consent.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tom Kennedy Departs |url=http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/news/article/tom-kennedy-departs-3126803.aspx?|publisher=Rochdale A.F.C.|accessdate=26 May 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516194606/http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/news/article/tom-kennedy-departs-3126803.aspx|archivedate=16 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Loan Spells====\nOn 23 October 2014, Kennedy rejoined [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] on loan from [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]] with a view to a permanent deal.<ref>{{cite web|title=TK returns to the JD Stadium|url=http://www.buryfc.co.uk/news/article/tk-returns-to-the-jd-stadium-2035081.aspx|publisher=Bury F.C.|accessdate=23 October 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624225805/http://www.buryfc.co.uk//news/article/tk-returns-to-the-jd-stadium-2035081.aspx|archivedate=24 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Two days later, Kennedy made his Bury debut, playing the whole game, in a 1\u20131 draw against [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]].<ref>{{cite news|title=FULL TIME REPORT: Southend United 1 Bury 1|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/sport/11559669.FULL_TIME__Southend_1_Bury_1/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=25 October 2014|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Just after making four appearance, Kennedy returned to his parent club on 22 November 2014 despite an option to extend until January.<ref>{{cite news|title=On-loan Bury defender Tom Kennedy set for quick return to Rochdale|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/sport/11605191.On_loan_Bury_defender_Tom_Kennedy_set_for_quick_return_to_Rochdale/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=16 November 2014|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bury loan deals for Everton striker Courtney Duffus and Rochdale defender Tom Kennedy cut short|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/sport/11620408.Bury_loan_deals_for_Everton_striker_Courtney_Duffus_and_Rochdale_defender_Tom_Kennedy_cut_short/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=22 November 2014|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 November 2014, Kennedy joined [[Football League Championship|Championship]] side [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] on loan until 14 January 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kennedy Arrives On Loan|url=http://www.blackpoolfc.co.uk/news/article/kennedy-arrives-on-loan-2097362.aspx?|publisher=Blackpool F.C.|accessdate=22 November 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920214526/http://www.blackpoolfc.co.uk//news/article/kennedy-arrives-on-loan-2097362.aspx|archivedate=20 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Later on the same day, he made his Blackpool debut, playing the whole game, in a 1\u20131 draw against [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Blackpool 1 \u2013 1 Bolton Wanderers|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/30065001|publisher=BBC Sport|date=22 November 2014|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Kennedy went on to make five appearance for the side, with his last appearance came on 20 December 2014, in a 6\u20131 heavy defeat to [[AFC Bournemouth|Bournemouth]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Blackpool 1 \u2013 6 AFC Bournemouth|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/30459467|publisher=BBC Sport|date=20 December 2014|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> After this, Kennedy was dropped from the squad and never played again.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blackpoolfc.co.uk/news/article/team-miller-and-davies-up-front-2164411.aspx|title=Team: Miller And Davies Up Front|publisher=Blackpool F.C.|date=26 December 2014|accessdate=16 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170515213112/http://www.blackpoolfc.co.uk/news/article/team-miller-and-davies-up-front-2164411.aspx|archivedate=15 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Eventually, Kennedy left Blackpool to return to his parent club in mid\u2013January.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chris Eagles leaves Blackpool after talks fail|url=http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/sport/football/blackpool-fc/eagles-leaves-blackpool-after-talks-fail-1-7058072|publisher=Blackpool Gazette|date=19 January 2015|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===AFC Fylde===\nAfter being released by Rochdale, Kennedy joined Non\u2013League side [[A.F.C. Fylde|AFC Fylde]] in the summer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afcfylde.co.uk/new-boy-tom-keeps-family/|title=NEW BOY TOM KEEPS IT IN THE FAMILY|publisher=AFC Fylde|date=10 August 2016|accessdate=16 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170515214526/http://www.afcfylde.co.uk/new-boy-tom-keeps-family/|archivedate=15 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nKennedy made his AFC Fylde debut, playing the whole game, in a 1\u20130 win over [[A.F.C. Telford United|Telford United]] in the opening game of the season.<ref>{{cite news|title=AFC TELFORD 0 AFC FYLDE 1: Report and reaction|url=http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/sport/football/afc-fylde/afc-telford-0-afc-fylde-1-report-and-reaction-1-8055546|publisher=Blackpool Gazette|date=6 August 2016|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Kennedy became a first team regular for the side and helped them win the National League North title after beating [[Boston United F.C.|Boston United]] on 22 April 2017.<ref>{{cite news|title= AFC Fylde crowned champions with 3-0 win at Boston United: Match report and reaction|url=http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/sport/football/afc-fylde/afc-fylde-crowned-champions-with-3-0-win-at-boston-united-match-report-and-reaction-1-8507302|publisher=Blackpool Gazette|date=23 April 2017|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> At the end of the 2016\u201317 season, Kennedy was among several players to leave the club.<ref>{{cite news|title= Champion Coasters ramp up player search|url=http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/sport/football/afc-fylde/champion-coasters-ramp-up-player-search-1-8538608|publisher=Blackpool Gazette|date=11 May 2017|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Tom Kennedy}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101207163937/http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/page/ProfilesDetail/0,,10441~22994,00.html Rochdale AFC Player Profile]\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards\n| bg = gold\n| fg = navy\n| list1 = \n{{2008\u201309 Football League Two Team of the Year}}\n{{2009\u201310 Football League Two Team of the Year}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kennedy, Tom}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Bury, Greater Manchester]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Bury F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Rochdale A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Leicester City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Peterborough United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Barnsley F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Blackpool F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bangor City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Cymru Premier players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Footballer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=June 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name            = Tom Kennedy\n| image           = Tomkennedy3.jpg\n| fullname        = Thomas Gordon Kennedy\n| height          = {{height|ft=5|in=11}}\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1985|6|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place     = [[Bury, Greater Manchester|Bury]], England\n| currentclub     = \n| clubnumber      = \n| position        = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| years1 = 2002\u20132007  | clubs1 = [[Bury F.C.|Bury]]                                          | caps1  = 143 | goals1  = 5\n| years2 = 2007\u20132010  | clubs2 = [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]]                                | caps2  = 137 | goals2  = 9\n| years3 = 2010\u20132012  | clubs3 = [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]]                      | caps3  = 6   | goals3  = 0\n| years4 = 2010\u20132011  | clubs4 = \u2192 [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]] (loan)                       | caps4  = 6   | goals4  = 0\n| years5 = 2011       | clubs5 = \u2192 [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]] (loan)   | caps5  = 14  | goals5  = 0\n| years6 = 2011       | clubs6 = \u2192 [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]] (loan)   | caps6  = 10  | goals6  = 0\n| years7 = 2012\u20132014  | clubs7 = [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]]                                  | caps7  = 68  | goals7  = 1\n| years8 = 2014\u20132016  | clubs8 = [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]]                                | caps8  = 41  | goals8  = 0\n| years9 = 2014       | clubs9 = \u2192 [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] (loan)                                 | caps9  = 2   | goals9  = 0\n| years10 = 2014\u20132015 | clubs10 = \u2192 [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] (loan)                      | caps10 = 5   | goals10 = 0\n| years11 = 2016\u20132017 | clubs11 = [[A.F.C. Fylde|AFC Fylde]]                                 | caps11 = 38  | goals11 = 0\n| years12 = 2017\u20132018 | clubs12 = [[Bangor City F.C.|Bangor City]]                           | caps12 = 27  | goals12 = 0\n| totalcaps = 497\n| totalgoals = 15\n| club-update =\n}}\n'''Thomas Gordon Kennedy''' (born 24 June 1985) is a former English professional [[Association football|footballer]]. Kennedy has had spells at [[Bury F.C.|Bury]], [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]], [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] and (on loan) [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]]. He mostly plays at [[Defender (association football)|left-back]]. In May 2018, he announced he was retiring from professional football after a spell at [[Bangor City F.C.|Bangor City]] in order to concentrate on his post-football career.\n\n==Club career==\nKennedy was born in Bury, England and grew up supporting his local team [[Bury F.C.|Bury]]. His father, Keith Kennedy, played for [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] while his uncle, [[Alan Kennedy]] was a [[Defender (football)|defender]] for [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] and [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Maden's double sends kids through|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5940837.Maden_s_double_sends_kids_through/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=29 October 2002|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Liverpool legend Alan Kennedy backs nephew Tom to be big hit at Leicester City|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/liverpool-legend-alan-kennedy-backs-nephew-tom-big-hit-leicester-city/story-12063994-detail/story.html|publisher=Leicester Mercury|date=15 June 2010|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs he started playing football, Kennedy revealed he started out playing in the central midfielder but as the years go by, he was pushed to playing out in different positions, leading him to play as a left-back, where he played today.<ref>{{cite news|title=Class is in the blood for Fylde's Tom Kennedy|url=http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/sport/football/afc-fylde/class-is-in-the-blood-for-fylde-s-kennedy-1-8060247|publisher=Blackpool Gazette|date=10 August 2016|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Bury===\nKennedy began his career at Bury and after progressing the ranks of Bury youth team,<ref>{{cite news|title=Nugent set for big time|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5926445.Nugent_set_for_big_time/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=31 December 2002|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Armstrong's debt to Bury youth policy|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5971305.Armstrong_s_debt_to_Bury_youth_policy/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=1 May 2002|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Kennedy signed a contract with the club in February 2003, keeping him until August 2004.<ref>{{cite news|title=Young guns ready to shoot to the top|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5914275.Young_guns_ready_to_shoot_to_the_top/|publisher=Bury Times|date=5 March 2003|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nHis impressive performance in the reserve earned him a first team in the 2003\u201304 season after being called\u2013up to the pre\u2013season tour with Bury.<ref>{{cite news|title=Stuart leaves Gigg to join Southend United|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5900058.Stuart_leaves_Gigg_to_join_Southend/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=5 June 2003|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Following this, Kennedy then made his debut as a 54th-minute substitute in Bury's 5\u20133 defeat away at [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]] on 16 September 2003.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bury FC: Shakers put through the Mill|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5881635.Bury_FC__Shakers_put_through_the_Mill/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=19 September 2003|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> His first start for Bury came in their 2\u20131 win over [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]] in the [[Football League Trophy]] on 3 November 2003.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thompson stakes his claim|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5873906.Thompson_stakes_his_claim/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=4 November 2003|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> His performance in the first team earned him Bury FC player-of-the-month for December.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bury FC: Tom's a chip off the old block|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5863244.Bury_FC__Tom_s_a_chip_off_the_old_block/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=9 January 2004|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> With 21 appearance in the first team, Kennedy signed a two-year contract with Bury.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kennedy signs new Bury deal|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bury/3579065.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=29 March 2004|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref> Kennedy then became Bury's first choice left back, starting all but one of Bury's remanding fixtures in the 2003\u201304 season, finish the season with 27 league appearances in his first full season at the club. At the end of the 2003\u201304 season, Kennedy was awarded the Young Player of the Year award.<ref>{{cite news|title=Glyn's glittering haul|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5839267.Glyn_s_glittering_haul/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=25 May 2004|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nDespite being linked a move away from Bury during and after the 2003\u201304 season,<ref>{{cite news|title=Barrow calls for Shakers focus by Phil Thorp|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5865508.Barrow_calls_for_Shakers_focus_by_Phil_Thorp/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=24 December 2003|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Kennedy boost for Shakers|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5850317.Kennedy_boost_for_Shakers/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=30 March 2004|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Kennedy stayed at the club for the 2004\u201305 season and was given a number three shirt.<ref>{{cite news|title=Newby gets his number|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5830082.Newby_gets_his_number/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=13 July 2004|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> After being told by the club's management that he would fight for the first team place, Kennedy managed to regained his first team place in the 2004\u201305 season and though he played in the left\u2013back position, he once played in the defensive midfield position.<ref>{{cite news|title=Shakers tough it out|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5830586.Shakers_tough_it_out/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=9 July 2004|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Shakers boss so excited about new venture|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5825439.Shakers_boss_so_excited_about_new_venture/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=9 August 2004|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=21 years, now Shakers dream of ending derby bogey|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5788664.21_years__now_Shakers_dream_of_ending_derby_bogey/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=1 April 2005|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Kennedy then scored his first goal, in a 2\u20132 draw away at [[Boston United F.C.|Boston United]] on 12 February 2005.<ref>{{cite news|title=Battling Shakers make their point|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5795105.Battling_Shakers_make_their_point/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=14 February 2005|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Despite the club's financial situation,<ref>{{cite news|title=Kennedy's pledge for the future|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5799966.Kennedy_s_pledge_for_the_future/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=18 January 2005|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Kennedy stayed and started all Bury's 46 games of the 2004\u201305 season scoring once, He made a total of 50 appearances, including making 46 league appearance, for Bury in all competitions throughout the season.\n\nIn the 2005\u201306 season, Kennedy continued to remain in the first team place and then scored his first goal of the season on 24 September 2005 in a 2\u20131 away defeat at [[Oxford United F.C.|Oxford United]] after coming on as a 59th-minute substitute.<ref>{{cite news|title=Casper optimistic despite defeat|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/6223680.Casper_optimistic_despite_defeat/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=24 September 2005|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Kennedy then scored in a 3\u20132 loss at home to [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] on 29 October 2005,<ref>{{cite news|title=Bury blunders prove so costly|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/6227085.Bury_blunders_prove_so_costly/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=29 October 2005|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> followed up by scoring a week later on 5 November 2005, in a 2\u20132 home draw with [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]] in the first round of the [[FA Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Cup stalemate as Bury play on Iron's failings: BURY 2, SCUNTHORPE UNITED 2|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/6228448.Cup_stalemate_as_Bury_play_on_Iron_s_failings__BURY_2__SCUNTHORPE_UNITED_2/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=10 November 2005|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> However, between December 2005 and March 2006, Kennedy spent the months sidelined when he suffered hamstring injuries on three occasions.<ref>{{cite news|title=Shakers aim to madden hatters!|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/6233509.Shakers_aim_to_madden_hatters_/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=29 December 2005|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bury bounce back thanks to Speight double|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/6235301.Bury_bounce_back_thanks_to_Speight_double/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=16 January 2006|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Boss sharpens up the Shakers|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/6235840.Boss_sharpens_up_the_Shakers/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=20 January 2006|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> After returning to the first team from injury against [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]] on 18 March 2006, coming on as a second-half substitute,<ref>{{cite news|title=Shot Shy Bury Pay The Price|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/710202.Shot_shy_Bury_pay_the_price/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=18 March 2006|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Kennedy scored his first goals in four months, in Bury's 1\u20131 draw at home with [[Oxford United F.C.|Oxford United]] on 21 March 2006.<ref>{{cite news|title=Shakers waste penalty gift|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/712618.Shakers_waste_penalty_gift/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=22 March 2006|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> On 8 April 2006, Kennedy later scored his fourth goal of the season, in a 3\u20131 loss at home to [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Casper Unhappy as Shakers Let It Slip|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/728136.Casper_unhappy_as_Shakers_let_it_slip/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=10 April 2006|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> In the 2005\u201306 season, Kennedy finished the season, making 35 appearances and scoring five times in all competitions. At the end of the 2005\u201306 season, Kennedy signed a one-year contract extension, keeping him until 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tom Kennedy signs on with the Shakers|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11774/2377817|publisher=Sky Sports|date=2 February 2007|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2006\u201307 season, Kennedy continued to be in the first team regular at Bury and then set up two goals, in a 2\u20132 draw against [[Accrington Stanley F.C.|Accrington Stanley]] on 26 September 2006.<ref>{{cite news|title=Match Report: Bury 2 \u2013 2 Accrington Stanley|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/942062.Bury_2_Accrington_Stanley_2/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=26 September 2006|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=You'll be the best \u2013 Casper|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/sport/978471.You_ll_be_the_best___Casper/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=19 October 2006|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Kennedy made his last appearances for The Shakers in their 1\u20130 home loss to [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] on 24 March 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=Another Defeat For Embattled Shakers|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/1286000.Another_defeat_for_embattled_Shaker/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=26 March 2007|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> However, as the 2006\u201307 season progressed, Kennedy went on to make thirty\u2013nine appearances and was released by the club at the end of the 2006\u201307 season, which he seek new challenges.<ref>{{cite news|title=Six go as Shakers announce clear-out|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/sport/1386837.Six_go_as_Shakers_announce_clear_out/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=9 May 2007|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Fresh start needed for Kennedy|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/sport/1387902.Fresh_start_needed_for_Kennedy/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=10 May 2007|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nKennedy left Bury in 2007 to join local rivals [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]] after making 158 appearances for his home town club scoring six times between 2003 when he made his debut for the club until 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rochdale sign Muirhead & Kennedy|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rochdale/6718723.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=4 June 2007|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref>  Additionally, Kennedy was able to surpass his father's goal tally while playing for Bury, a prediction he made two years ago.<ref>{{cite news|title=Teenage Shaker has his dad's tally in sight|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/5795010.Teenage_Shaker_has_his_dad_s_tally_in_sight/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=18 February 2005|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Rochdale===\n[[File:tomkennedy.jpg|thumb|150px|Kennedy playing for Rochdale in March 2015.]]\n\nKennedy signed for Rochdale on 4 June 2007 after four seasons at Bury.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rochdale sign Muirhead & Kennedy|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rochdale/6718723.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=4 June 2007|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nKennedy made his debut, in the opening game of the season on 11 August 2007, in a 3\u20130 loss against [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Reality check for Dale in season opener|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/2341/reality-check-for-dale-in-season-opener|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=11 August 2007|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Since making his Rochdale debut, Kennedy quickly became a first team regular, playing in the left\u2013back position.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hill warns players to expect a tough match against Wrexham|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/933/hill-warns-players-to-expect-a-tough-match-against-wrexham|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=30 November 2007|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> After suffering an illness that saw him missed one match in late\u2013December,<ref>{{cite news|title=Dale manager Hill confident of extending six match unbeaten run|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/887/dale-manager-hill-confident-of-extending-six-match-unbeaten-run|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=31 December 2007|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Kennedy returned from injury and set up one of the goals, in a 3\u20131 win over [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]] on 1 January 2008,<ref>{{cite news|title=First half strikes sink Darlington|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/22/first-half-strikes-sink-darlington|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=1 January 2008|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> followed up by scoring his first goal for the club, in a 1\u20130 win over [[Wycombe Wanderers F.C.|Wycombe Wanderers]] on 11 January 2008.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wycombe Wanderers 0\u20131 Rochdale|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/7172946.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=11 January 2008|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref> He scored his second goal of the season on 29 January 2008, in a 4\u20130 win over [[Chester F.C.|Chester]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Ellison sees red to make it all too easy for Dale|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/583/ellison-sees-red-to-make-it-all-too-easy-for-dale|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=29 January 2008|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> In the [[2008 Football League play-offs|play-offs]] against [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Kennedy looking forward to derby|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/8451/kennedy-looking-forward-to-derby|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=23 April 2008|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Kennedy scored the second penalty in a penalty shoot-out and Rochdale would win the game to go to the [[2008 Football League Two play-off Final|final]] to face [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]], after [[Jason Kennedy (footballer)|Jason Kennedy]] miss the final spot kick. After the match, Kennedy reflected the 2007\u201308 season, stating that the club have had an 'amazing' season and described this an unbelievable feeling.<ref>{{cite news|title=Amazing season for Dale \u2013 Kennedy|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rochdale/7408572.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=19 May 2008|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref> However, Rochdale would succumb 3\u20132 to Stockport County, remaining in League Two for the following season. Despite this, he went on to finish his first season, making 46 appearances (43 in the league) and scoring two times in all competitions.\n\nIn the 2008\u201309 season, Kennedy started the season well when he helped the side go to their winning ways following the play\u2013offs defeat to Stockport County<ref>{{cite news|title=Dale ready for season opener|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/12632/dale-ready-for-season-opener|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=7 August 2008|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> and scored a winning goal from a free kick in stoppage time, in a 2\u20131 win over [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]] on 20 September 2008.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rochdale 2 \u2013 1 Chesterfield|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_div_3/7614072.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=20 September 2008|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> It wasn't until on 23 January 2009 when he scored his second goal of the season, in a 3\u20132 loss against [[Dagenham & Redbridge F.C.|Dagenham & Redbridge]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Dagenham & Redbridge 3 \u2013 2 Rochdale|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/7844330.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=23 January 2009|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> A week later, Kennedy signed a contract extension, keeping him until the end of the 2009\u201310 season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dale duo extend deals|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11750/4888749|publisher=Sky Sports|date=2 February 2009|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref> Following this, he scored two more goals later in the season against [[Macclesfield Town F.C.|Macclesfield Town]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Macclesfield Town 0 \u2013 1 Rochdale|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/7876781.st|publisher=BBC Sport|date=14 February 2009|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> and [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Rochdale 1 (Kennedy 37 pen) Brentford 2 (Rhodes 9, MacDonald 15) \u2013 Full Time Report|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/viewer?NewsID=20464|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=24 February 2009|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Since the start of the season, Kennedy featured in every league game until he missed out on the last game of the season, due to resting ahead of the play\u2013offs.<ref>{{cite news|title=Can Dale end 35 year wait?|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/23739/can-dale-end-35-year-wait|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=7 May 2009|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> However, once again, Rochdale lost 2\u20131 on aggregate to [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Gillingham 2 (Jackson 13, 58 pen) Rochdale 1 (Dagnall 36) - Full Time Report|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/23808/gillingham-2-jackson-13-58-pen-rochdale-1-dagnall-36-full-time-report|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=10 May 2009|accessdate=17 May 2017}}</ref> Despite this, Kennedy was voted into the PFA League Two Team of The Year, voted for by his fellow professionals in League Two, for the 2008\u201309 season at the PFA awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10441~1645190,00.html|title=Hilly in Praise of TK|publisher=Rochdale AFC official website|date=1 May 2009|accessdate=1 May 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090502233424/http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10441~1645190,00.html|archivedate=2 May 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> He was also voted Defender of the Year for the 2008\u201309 season following Rochdale's unsuccessful promotion push.<ref>{{cite news|title=Supporters Trust donates \u00a31330 for pre-season tour|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/24206/supporters-trust-donates-\u00a31330-for-preseason-tour|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=18 May 2009|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2009\u201310 season, Kennedy started the season well when he scored the only goal in the game from a penalty, in a 1\u20130 win over [[Aldershot Town F.C.|Aldershot Town]] on 15 August 2009.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rochdale 1 (T. Kennedy 90 pen) Aldershot 0 \u2013 Full Time Report|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/28421/rochdale-1-t-kennedy-90-pen-aldershot-0-%E2%80%93-full-time-report|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=15 August 2009|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> He later scored two more goals by the end of the 2009 against Bury<ref>{{cite news|title=16 years of derby day hurt end in fine style|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/29019/16-years-of-derby-day-hurt-end-in-fine-style|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=30 August 2009|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> and [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Rochdale 2 \u2013 1 Barnet|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/8293297.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=10 October 2009|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> His performance throughout the 2009\u201310 season led Manager [[Keith Hill (footballer)|Keith Hill]] commented in March 2010 that Kennedy is considered as the best left-back in League Two.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rochdale boss Keith Hill praises Tom Kennedy|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rochdale/8570326.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=16 March 2010|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref> After helping the club finished third place that saw them promoted to League One, Kennedy finished the 2009\u201310 season, making 47 (44 in the league) appearances and scoring three times in all competitions. Once again, Kennedy was voted into the PFA League Two Team of The Year for the 2009\u201310 season at the PFA awards.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rooney is PFA player of the year|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/8643305.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=25 April 2010|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the season, Kennedy was offered a new contract by the club, as his contract set to expires in July.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dales Release Players|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/41053/dale-release-players|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=13 May 2010|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> However, he announced his intention to leave Rochdale,<ref>{{cite news|title=Kennedy set for Dale exit|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11715/6176739|publisher=Sky Sports|date=28 May 2010|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref> with clubs in Championship like [[Doncaster Rovers F.C.|Doncaster Rovers]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Rovers eye Rochdale raid|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/6136315|publisher=Sky Sports|date=13 May 2010|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref> [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]], [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]] all tracking to sign Kennedy.\n\n===Leicester City===\nOn 10 June 2010, the [[Football League Championship|Championship]] side [[Leicester City FC|Leicester City]] agreed a pre-contract with Kennedy and the left back officially joined Leicester on 1 July,<ref name=\"Foxes grab Kennedy\">{{Cite web| title=Foxes Grab Kennedy| url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11688_6199418,00.html| publisher=British Sky Broadcasting| work=www.skysports.com| date=10 June 2010| accessdate=10 June 2010}}</ref> having rejected a chance to move Doncaster Rovers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kennedy set for Rovers|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/6190633|publisher=Sky Sports|date=4 June 2010|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref> After moving, Kennedy say he made an easy decision to join Leicester City.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tom Kennedy says Leicester City switch was easy|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/leicester_city/8734631.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=11 June 2010|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nKennedy made his Leicester City debut in the first round of the League Cup, starting the whole game, in a 4\u20133 win over [[Macclesfield Town F.C.|Macclesfield Town]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Leicester City edge out Macclesfield Town in Carling Cup clash|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/leicester-city-edge-macclesfield-carling-cup-clash/story-12027572-detail/story.html|publisher=Leicester Mercury|date=11 August 2010|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> It wasn't until on 28 September 2010 when he made his league debut for the club away, in a 4\u20133 loss against [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]], playing the whole game.<ref>{{cite news|title=Norwich City 4 \u2013 3 Leicester City|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/9031746.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=28 September 2010|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> During the match, he was conceded a penalty when he was penalised for handball.<ref>{{cite news|title=Match verdict: Battling Leicester City rue defensive errors against Norwich City|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/match-verdict-battling-leicester-city-rue-defensive-errors-norwich/story-12081213-detail/story.html|publisher=Leicester Mercy|date=29 September 2010|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> After the match, Kennedy acknowledged the fault of giving away the penalty, but hopes for first team football in the near future.<ref>{{cite news|title=Defender Tom Kennedy says it's down to Leicester City players to stop the rot|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/s-stop-rot/story-12080758-detail/story.html|publisher=Leicester Mercury|date=30 September 2010|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Despite stating that he adapted to the team,<ref>{{cite news|title=Defender Tom Kennedy has vowed that Leicester City fans are in for a treat|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/tom-kennedy-says-leicester-city-fans-treat/story-12038366-detail/story.html|publisher=Leicester Mercury|date=19 July 2010|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> his time at Leicester City was unhappy over lack of first team opportunities at Leicester City as he spent time on the bench more often, as well as, becoming the third choice player in the left\u2013back position behind [[Bruno Berner]] and [[Greg Cunningham]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Frustrated Tom Kennedy is glad to be on the move from Leicester City|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/frustrated-tom-kennedy-glad-leicester-city/story-12055761-detail/story.html|publisher=Leicester Mercury|date=3 November 2010|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> In his first season at Leicester City, Kennedy went on to make four appearances in all competitions.\n\nAhead of the 2011\u201312 season, Kennedy stated that he has no future at Leicester City.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tom Kennedy looks at life away from Leicester City|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/tom-kennedy-looks-life-away-leicester-city/story-12082573-detail/story.html|publisher=Leicester Mercury|date=1 April 2011|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> After returning from a loan spell at Peterborough United, Kennedy returned to Leicester City<ref name=\"Kennedy Peterborough Telegraph\"/> and was put straight into the starting line-up against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] to finally make his senior debut for the club under [[Nigel Pearson]], 19 months after signing him.<ref>{{cite news|title=Leicester City back to winning ways|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/leicester-city-winning-ways/story-14303368-detail/story.html|publisher=Leicester Mercury|date=2 January 2012|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Though he made seven more appearances in all competitions later in the season, his first team opportunities continued to be limited, as he spent the rest of the season on the substitute bench.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kennedy presses his claim to start|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/kennedy-presses-claim-start/story-15384773-detail/story.html|publisher=Leicester Mercury|date=3 March 2012|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> As a result, it was announced that Kennedy and the club came to a mutual agreement to terminate his contract on 29 August 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tom Kennedy set to move on from Leicester City|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/8029924|publisher=Sky Sports|date=29 August 2012|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Loan moves====\nOn 1 November 2010, Kennedy rejoined his old club Rochdale on loan until January due to lack of first team opportunities at Leicester City.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kennedy makes Rochdale return|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11719/6481525|publisher=Sky Sports|date=1 November 2010|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref> Kennedy's first match since leaving the club in the summer came on 13 November 2010, starting the whole, in a 2\u20130 loss against [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Match Report: Sheffield Wednesday 2 \u2013 0 Rochdale|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/49283/sheffield-wednesday-2-0-rochdale|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=13 November 2010|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> In the next game against [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] on 20 November 2010, Kennedy set up one of the goals, in a 3\u20133 draw.<ref>{{cite news|title=Match Report: Rochdale 3 \u2013 3 Swindon Town|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/49551/rochdale-3-3-swindon-town|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=20 November 2010|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> After making six appearance at Rochdale, Kennedy loan spell at Rochdale had ended in January 2011.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kennedy returns from loan spell|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11765/6651094|publisher=Sky Sports|date=11 January 2011|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 January 2011, Kennedy joined [[Football League One|League One]] club [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]] on loan until the end of the season, which could be made permanent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lcfc.com/page/LatestNews/0,,10274~2271424,00.html|title=Kennedy joins Peterborough United on Loan|publisher=LCFC.com|date=20 January 2011|accessdate=20 January 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110121162847/http://www.lcfc.com/page/LatestNews/0,,10274~2271424,00.html|archivedate=21 January 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The next day, on 21 January 2011, Kennedy made his debut, playing 90 minutes, in a 4\u20130 win over [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Posh 4, Hartlepool 0 \u2013 Happy return for Darren Ferguson|url=http://www.peterboroughtoday.co.uk/sport/football/posh/posh-4-hartlepool-0-happy-return-for-ferguson-1-2335660|publisher=Peterborough Today|date=21 January 2011|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Kennedy have since established himself in the starting eleven, playing in the left back position in defence. Having made 14 starts since joining the club, Kennedy said he expressed desire to stay at Peterborough United permanent at the end of the season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kennedy keen on Posh stay|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11712/6843100|publisher=Sky Sports|date=30 March 2011|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref> But, nothing came for it as in April, Kennedy suffered a knee ligament damage during a 2\u20130 win over [[Dagenham & Redbridge F.C.|Dagenham & Redbridge]], resulted his last appearance for Peterborough and would return to Leicester City for treatment.<ref>{{cite news|title=Peterborough United hit by Tom Kennedy knee injury|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/13039528|publisher=BBC Sport|date=11 April 2011|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref> At the end of the season with Peterborough promoted to the Championship, director of football [[Barry Fry]] expressed desire to sign Kennedy but feared his injury prevent his move back to the club<ref>{{cite news|title=Posh keen on duo's return|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11688/6963655|publisher=Sky Sports|date=2 June 2011|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 September 2011, Kennedy re-joined Peterborough for a second loan spell on a 3-month loan from Leicester.<ref>{{cite news|title=Leicester City's Tom Kennedy returns to Peterborough United|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/15126916|publisher=BBC Sport|date=30 September 2011|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref> However, Kennedy's first month at re\u2013joining the club suffered a setback, as he became a second choice left\u2013back player behind [[Craig Alcock]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Posh preview: Bristol City will be a team of wounded animal|url=http://www.peterboroughtoday.co.uk/sport/football/posh/posh-preview-bristol-city-will-be-a-team-of-wounded-animals-1-3151728|publisher=Peterborough Today|date=14 October 2011|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=POSH HOPING TO KEEP RYAN|url=http://www.peterboroughtoday.co.uk/sport/football/posh/posh-hoping-to-keep-ryan-1-3196677|publisher=Peterborough Today|date=29 October 2011|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> It wasn't until on 30 October 2011 when Kennedy made his second debut for the club, playing the whole game, in a 3\u20132 loss against [[Watford F.C.|Watford]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Watford 3 Posh 2: It's captain non-sensible!|url=http://www.peterboroughtoday.co.uk/sport/football/posh/watford-3-posh-2-it-s-captain-non-sensible-1-3200180|publisher=Peterborough Today|date=30 October 2011|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> After making ten appearance for the side in his second loan spell, Kennedy's second loan at Peterborough ended in January 2012.<ref name=\"Kennedy Peterborough Telegraph\">{{cite news|title=POSH MAKING FERGIE PROUD|url=http://www.peterboroughtoday.co.uk/sport/football/peterborough-united/posh-making-fergie-proud-1-3380400|publisher=Peterborough Today|date=2 January 2012|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Barnsley===\nAfter leaving Leicester City, Kennedy agreed non-contract terms with [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] until January 2013 on 21 September 2012 after a period training with the [[South Yorkshire]] club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-league.co.uk/championship/news/20120921/kennedy-completes-tykes-switch_2293322_2925868|title=Kennedy completes Tykes switch|publisher=The Football League|date=21 September 2012|accessdate=16 January 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715002149/http://www.football-league.co.uk/championship/news/20120921/kennedy-completes-tykes-switch_2293322_2925868|archivedate=15 July 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nKennedy made his debut on 22 September in a 5\u20130 win against [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19615055 \"Birmingham 0\u20135 Barnsley\"] BBC Sport. 22 September 2012. Retrieved 29 September 2012.</ref> However Kennedy initially struggled for first team opportunities, making just a handful of first team appearances; but since early January became a first team regular for the rest of the season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Barnsley: Tom Kennedy is ready to get ugly|url=http://www.thestar.co.uk/sport/football/sheffield-united/barnsley-tom-is-ready-to-get-ugly-1-5416774|publisher=The Star|date=16 February 2013|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> As a result, Kennedy signed a six-month contract as his non-contract agreement was about to expire.<ref>{{cite news|title=Barnsley: Defender gets six months Reds' deal|url=http://www.thestar.co.uk/sport/football/barnsley/barnsley-defender-gets-six-months-reds-deal-1-5321234|publisher=The Star|date=17 January 2013|accessdate=17 January 2013}}</ref> In a 6\u20130 loss against [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] on 13 April 2013, he received a straight red card when he \"brought down [[Ricardo Fuller]]\" and was the second Barnsley to be sent\u2013off in the game, as well as [[Stephen Dawson]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Football League Championship: Charlton Athletic hammer Barnsley 6 \u2013 0 at Oakwell|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/barnsley-vs-charlton/262180|publisher=Sky Sports|date=13 April 2013|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> He served a one\u2013match suspension<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barnsleyfc.co.uk/news/article/flitcroft-on-forest-clash-18042013-779968.aspx|title=Flitcroft on Nottingham Forest Clash|publisher=Barnsley F.C.|date=18 April 2013|accessdate=16 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170515201604/http://www.barnsleyfc.co.uk/news/article/flitcroft-on-forest-clash-18042013-779968.aspx|archivedate=15 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and returned to the first team, where he played three remaining matches later in the season, including the last game of the season, playing the whole game, in a 2\u20132 draw against [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]], a draw that saw Barnsley secure Championship status for another season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barnsleyfc.co.uk/news/article/the-reds-are-staying-up-807660.aspx|title=The Reds Are Staying Up!|publisher=Barnsley F.C.|date=4 May 2013|accessdate=16 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170515201511/http://www.barnsleyfc.co.uk/news/article/the-reds-are-staying-up-807660.aspx|archivedate=15 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> At the end of the 2012\u201313 season, Kennedy went on to make 24 appearances in all competitions and for his performance, Kennedy signed a two-year extension in the summer of 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=Barnsley: Tom Kennedy signs a new two-year deal at Oakwell|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22690879|publisher=BBC Sport|date=28 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2013\u201314 season, Kennedy switched number shirt from 33 to 4 this season<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barnsleyfc.co.uk/news/article/squad-numbers-28062013-885508.aspx|title=Squad Numbers|publisher=Barnsley F.C.|date=28 June 2013|accessdate=16 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170515202516/http://www.barnsleyfc.co.uk/news/article/squad-numbers-28062013-885508.aspx|archivedate=15 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and continued to be a first team regular for the side since the start of the season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Barnsley: Reds starlet backed to fulfil potential|url=http://www.thestar.co.uk/sport/football/barnsley-fc/barnsley-reds-starlet-backed-to-fulfil-potential-1-6016456|publisher=The Star|date=6 September 2013|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> In a 2\u20131 win over Huddersfield Town on 31 August 2013, he set up a goal for [[Marcus Pedersen]] to score the second goal for Barnsley in the game.<ref>{{cite news|title=Barnsley 2 \u2013 1 Huddersfield Town|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23822875|publisher=BBC Sport|date=31 August 2013|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Kennedy also assisted six more times later in the 2013\u201314 season, including assisting a winning goal, in a 1\u20130 win over [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] on 8 March 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=Barnsley 1 \u2013 0 Nottingham Forest|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/26395407|publisher=BBC Sport|date=8 March 2014|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Kennedy then scored his first goal for the club on 15 April 2014, scoring a winning goal, in a 2\u20131 against Charlton Athletic.<ref>{{cite news|title=Charlton Athletic 1 \u2013 2 Barnsley|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25817450|publisher=BBC Sport|date=15 April 2014|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> However, the club was eventually relegated to League One next season after losing 3\u20131 to [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] on 26 April 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=Middlesbrough 3 \u2013 1 Barnsley|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/27084041|publisher=BBC Sport|date=26 April 2014|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Despite missing out two times, due to being on the substitute bench unused, Kennedy finished his second season at Barnsley, making forty\u2013seven appearances and scoring once in all competitions.\n\nHowever, ahead of the 2014\u201315 season, Kennedy terminated his contract at Barnsley on 31 July 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barnsleyfc.co.uk/news/article/tom-kennedy-leaves-oakwell-30072014-1793231.aspx|title=Tom Kennedy Leaves Oakwell|publisher=Barnsley F.C.|date=31 July 2014|accessdate=16 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170515203819/http://www.barnsleyfc.co.uk/news/article/tom-kennedy-leaves-oakwell-30072014-1793231.aspx|archivedate=15 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> It came after when Kennedy, along with [[Martin Cranie]], did not travel to Italy with the squad for the club's pre-season training trip to Italy.<ref>{{cite news|title=Barnsley: Steele and O'Grady add to exodus|url=http://www.thestar.co.uk/sport/football/barnsley-fc/barnsley-steele-and-o-grady-add-to-exodus-1-6738529|publisher=The Star|date=18 July 2014|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Rochdale Return===\nOn 14 August 2014, Kennedy resigned for [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]] on a short term deal until January 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tom Kennedy Returns To Rochdale|url=http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/news/article/tk-signs-1828999.aspx|publisher=Rochdale A.F.C.|accessdate=14 August 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516184745/http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/news/article/tk-signs-1828999.aspx|archivedate=16 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and reuniting with former manager Keith Hill.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/news/article/hill-tkdawson-1831034.aspx|title=Hill: Dawson & Kennedy|publisher=Rochdale A.F.C.|date=15 August 2014|accessdate=16 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516185000/http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/news/article/hill-tkdawson-1831034.aspx|archivedate=16 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nTwo days after signing for the club, Kennedy's second debut for the club came against Chesterfield, playing the whole game, in a 2\u20131 loss.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chesterfield 2 \u2013 1 Rochdale|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/28716649|publisher=BBC Sport|date=16 August 2014|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Although becoming a first team regular throughout August, Kennedy lost his first team place in the left\u2013back positions and was limited to six appearances by the time he went out on loan throughout January.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tom Kennedy out on loan to Bury|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/92106/tom-kennedy-out-on-loan-to-bury|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=24 October 2014|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> After returning to his parent club from loan spells, he signed a contract extension with the club, keeping him until the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/news/article/tom-kennedy-signs-contract-2273837.aspx|title=Tom Kennedy Signs Contract|publisher=Rochdale A.F.C.|date=16 February 2015|accessdate=16 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516191440/http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/news/article/tom-kennedy-signs-contract-2273837.aspx|archivedate=16 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> It wasn't until on 21 February 2015 when he returned to the first team for the first time since October, playing the whole game, in a 1\u20130 win over Chesterfield.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rochdale 1 \u2013 0 Chesterfield|url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/4/sport-news/94358/rochdale-1-0-chesterfield|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=21 February 2015|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Since then, Kennedy regained his first team place as a left\u2013back throughout the 2014\u201315 season, making twenty\u2013four appearances in all competitions and it was announced on 29 June 2015 that Kennedy signed a new two-year deal.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tom Kennedy Signs New Contract|url=http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/news/article/tom-kennedy-signs-new-contract-2510937.aspx?|publisher=Rochdale A.F.C.|accessdate=29 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516192704/http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/news/article/tom-kennedy-signs-new-contract-2510937.aspx|archivedate=16 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn his second season at Rochdale, Kennedy continued to regain his first team place at the start of the 2015\u201316 season, but soon around October, he was demoted to the substitute for the most of the season, due to competitions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/news/article/injury-update-ashley-eastham-2903420.aspx|title=Injury Update: Ashley Eastham|publisher=Rochdale A.F.C.|date=15 January 2016|accessdate=16 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516193645/http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/news/article/injury-update-ashley-eastham-2903420.aspx|archivedate=16 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> After returning to the first team in January, Kennedy made his 200th appearance in his Rochdale career on 30 January 2016, in a 2\u20131 win over [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/news/article/appearance-milestones-for-tom-kennedy-olly-lancashire-2932659.aspx|title=Appearance Milestones For Tom Kennedy & Olly Lancashire|publisher=Rochdale A.F.C.|date=1 February 2016|accessdate=16 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516193656/http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/news/article/appearance-milestones-for-tom-kennedy-olly-lancashire-2932659.aspx|archivedate=16 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> However, Kennedy, once again, lost his first team place at Rochdale and didn't play again for the rest of the 2015\u201316 season. Despite this, he went on to make twenty\u2013one appearances in all competitions.\n\nOn 26 May 2016, Kennedy left Rochdale by mutual consent.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tom Kennedy Departs |url=http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/news/article/tom-kennedy-departs-3126803.aspx?|publisher=Rochdale A.F.C.|accessdate=26 May 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516194606/http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/news/article/tom-kennedy-departs-3126803.aspx|archivedate=16 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Loan Spells====\nOn 23 October 2014, Kennedy rejoined [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] on loan from [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]] with a view to a permanent deal.<ref>{{cite web|title=TK returns to the JD Stadium|url=http://www.buryfc.co.uk/news/article/tk-returns-to-the-jd-stadium-2035081.aspx|publisher=Bury F.C.|accessdate=23 October 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624225805/http://www.buryfc.co.uk//news/article/tk-returns-to-the-jd-stadium-2035081.aspx|archivedate=24 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Two days later, Kennedy made his Bury debut, playing the whole game, in a 1\u20131 draw against [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]].<ref>{{cite news|title=FULL TIME REPORT: Southend United 1 Bury 1|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/sport/11559669.FULL_TIME__Southend_1_Bury_1/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=25 October 2014|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Just after making four appearance, Kennedy returned to his parent club on 22 November 2014 despite an option to extend until January.<ref>{{cite news|title=On-loan Bury defender Tom Kennedy set for quick return to Rochdale|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/sport/11605191.On_loan_Bury_defender_Tom_Kennedy_set_for_quick_return_to_Rochdale/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=16 November 2014|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bury loan deals for Everton striker Courtney Duffus and Rochdale defender Tom Kennedy cut short|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/sport/11620408.Bury_loan_deals_for_Everton_striker_Courtney_Duffus_and_Rochdale_defender_Tom_Kennedy_cut_short/|publisher=The Bury Times|date=22 November 2014|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 November 2014, Kennedy joined [[Football League Championship|Championship]] side [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] on loan until 14 January 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kennedy Arrives On Loan|url=http://www.blackpoolfc.co.uk/news/article/kennedy-arrives-on-loan-2097362.aspx?|publisher=Blackpool F.C.|accessdate=22 November 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920214526/http://www.blackpoolfc.co.uk//news/article/kennedy-arrives-on-loan-2097362.aspx|archivedate=20 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Later on the same day, he made his Blackpool debut, playing the whole game, in a 1\u20131 draw against [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Blackpool 1 \u2013 1 Bolton Wanderers|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/30065001|publisher=BBC Sport|date=22 November 2014|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Kennedy went on to make five appearance for the side, with his last appearance came on 20 December 2014, in a 6\u20131 heavy defeat to [[AFC Bournemouth|Bournemouth]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Blackpool 1 \u2013 6 AFC Bournemouth|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/30459467|publisher=BBC Sport|date=20 December 2014|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> After this, Kennedy was dropped from the squad and never played again.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blackpoolfc.co.uk/news/article/team-miller-and-davies-up-front-2164411.aspx|title=Team: Miller And Davies Up Front|publisher=Blackpool F.C.|date=26 December 2014|accessdate=16 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170515213112/http://www.blackpoolfc.co.uk/news/article/team-miller-and-davies-up-front-2164411.aspx|archivedate=15 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Eventually, Kennedy left Blackpool to return to his parent club in mid\u2013January.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chris Eagles leaves Blackpool after talks fail|url=http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/sport/football/blackpool-fc/eagles-leaves-blackpool-after-talks-fail-1-7058072|publisher=Blackpool Gazette|date=19 January 2015|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===AFC Fylde===\nAfter being released by Rochdale, Kennedy joined Non\u2013League side [[A.F.C. Fylde|AFC Fylde]] in the summer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afcfylde.co.uk/new-boy-tom-keeps-family/|title=NEW BOY TOM KEEPS IT IN THE FAMILY|publisher=AFC Fylde|date=10 August 2016|accessdate=16 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170515214526/http://www.afcfylde.co.uk/new-boy-tom-keeps-family/|archivedate=15 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nKennedy made his AFC Fylde debut, playing the whole game, in a 1\u20130 win over [[A.F.C. Telford United|Telford United]] in the opening game of the season.<ref>{{cite news|title=AFC TELFORD 0 AFC FYLDE 1: Report and reaction|url=http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/sport/football/afc-fylde/afc-telford-0-afc-fylde-1-report-and-reaction-1-8055546|publisher=Blackpool Gazette|date=6 August 2016|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Kennedy became a first team regular for the side and helped them win the National League North title after beating [[Boston United F.C.|Boston United]] on 22 April 2017.<ref>{{cite news|title= AFC Fylde crowned champions with 3-0 win at Boston United: Match report and reaction|url=http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/sport/football/afc-fylde/afc-fylde-crowned-champions-with-3-0-win-at-boston-united-match-report-and-reaction-1-8507302|publisher=Blackpool Gazette|date=23 April 2017|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> At the end of the 2016\u201317 season, Kennedy was among several players to leave the club.<ref>{{cite news|title= Champion Coasters ramp up player search|url=http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/sport/football/afc-fylde/champion-coasters-ramp-up-player-search-1-8538608|publisher=Blackpool Gazette|date=11 May 2017|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Tom Kennedy}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101207163937/http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/page/ProfilesDetail/0,,10441~22994,00.html Rochdale AFC Player Profile]\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards\n| bg = gold\n| fg = navy\n| list1 = \n{{2008\u201309 Football League Two Team of the Year}}\n{{2009\u201310 Football League Two Team of the Year}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kennedy, Tom}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Bury, Greater Manchester]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Bury F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Rochdale A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Leicester City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Peterborough United F.C. players]]\n